# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: mudbrick
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:mudbrick/abri-de-la-madeleine] The archaeological site **Abri de la Madeleine** (Magdalene Shelter) is a rock shelter under an overhanging cliff situated near Tursac, in the Dordogne *département* of the Aquitaine région of southwestern France.
[src:mudbrick/abri-de-la-madeleine] It represents the type site of the Magdalenian culture of the Upper Paleolithic.
[src:mudbrick/abri-de-la-madeleine] The shelter was also occupied during the Middle Ages.
[src:mudbrick/abri-de-la-madeleine] The medieval castle of Petit Marsac stands on the top of the cliff just above the shelter.
[src:mudbrick/abri-de-la-madeleine] Édouard Lartet, financed and helped by the Englishman Henry Christy, were the first systematic excavators of the site, starting in 1863, and published their findings in 1875 under the name of the Age of the Reindeer ("L'âge du renne").
[src:mudbrick/abri-de-la-madeleine] Objects that were found at the **la Madeleine** site are distributed among a number of museums, including the Muséum de Toulouse, the Musee des Antiquites Nationales, St.
[src:mudbrick/abri-de-la-madeleine] The Abri de la Madeleine is classified as a *Monument historique* since 1956.
[src:mudbrick/abri-de-la-madeleine] In 1979, the Abri de la Madeleine was inscribed on the UNESCO World Heritage List as part of the *Prehistoric Sites and Decorated Caves of the Vézère Valley* because of its unique paleolithic artwork and archeological importance.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] Acheulean tools were produced during the Lower Palaeolithic era across Africa and much of West Asia, South Asia, East Asia and Europe, and are typically found with *Homo erectus* remains.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] It is thought that Acheulean technologies first developed about 2 million years ago, derived from the more primitive Oldowan technology associated with *Homo habilis*.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] The Acheulean includes at least the early part of the Middle Paleolithic.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] Its end is not well defined; if Sangoan (also known as Epi-Acheulean) is included, it may be taken to last until as late as 130,000 years ago.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] In Europe and Western Asia, early Neanderthals utilized Acheulean technology, later transitioning to the more advanced Mousterian beginning around 320,000 years ago.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] The type site for the Acheulean is Saint-Acheul, a suburb of Amiens, the capital of the Somme department in Picardy, where artifacts were found in 1859.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] John Frere is generally credited as being the first to suggest a very ancient date for Acheulean hand-axes.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] In 1797, he sent two examples to the Royal Academy in London from Hoxne in Suffolk.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] He had found them in prehistoric lake deposits along with the bones of extinct animals and concluded that they were made by people "who had not the use of metals" and that they belonged to a "very ancient period indeed, even beyond the present world".
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] His ideas were, however, ignored by his contemporaries, who subscribed to a pre-Darwinian view of human evolution.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] Later, Jacques Boucher de Crèvecœur de Perthes, working between 1836 and 1846, collected further examples of hand-axes and fossilised animal bone from the gravel river terraces of the Somme near Abbeville in northern France.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] Again, his theories attributing great antiquity to the finds were spurned by his colleagues, until one of de Perthes' main opponents, Marcel Jérôme Rigollot, began finding more tools near Saint Acheul.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] Following visits to both Abbeville and Saint Acheul by the geologist Joseph Prestwich, the age of the tools was finally accepted.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] In 1872, Louis Laurent Gabriel de Mortillet described the characteristic hand-axe tools as belonging to *L'Epoque de St Acheul*.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] The industry was renamed as the Acheulean in 1925.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] Providing calendrical dates and ordered chronological sequences in the study of early stone tool manufacture is often accomplished through one or more geological techniques, such as radiometric dating, often potassium-argon dating, and magnetostratigraphy.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] From the Konso Formation of Ethiopia, Acheulean hand-axes are dated to about 1.5 million years ago using radiometric dating of deposits containing volcanic ashes.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] Acheulean tools in South Asia have also been found to be dated as far as 1.5 million years ago.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] However, in 2003 examples of the Acheulean from the West Turkana region of Kenya were described which have been dated through the method of magnetostratigraphy to about 1.76 million years ago, and in 2023 finds from Ethiopia were reported dating to 1.95 million years ago.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] The earliest user of Acheulean tools may have been *Homo ergaster*, who first appeared about 1.8 million years ago (not all researchers use this formal name, and instead prefer to call these users *early Homo erectus*).
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] However, it is impossible to know for sure whether *Homo ergaster* was the only maker of early Acheulean tools, since other hominin species, such as *Homo habilis*, also lived in East Africa at this time.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] From geological dating of sedimentary deposits, it appears that the Acheulean originated in Africa and spread to Asian, Middle Eastern, and European areas sometime between 1.5 million years ago and about 800 thousand years ago.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] In individual regions, this dating can be considerably refined; in Europe for example, it was thought that Acheulean methods did not reach the continent until around 500,000 years ago.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] However, more recent research demonstrated that hand-axes from Spain were made more than 900,000 years ago.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] It is therefore important not to see the Acheulean as a neatly defined period or one that happened as part of a clear sequence but as one tool-making technique that flourished especially well in early prehistory.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] The enormous geographic spread of Acheulean techniques also makes the name unwieldy as it represents numerous regional variations on a similar theme.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] The term Acheulean does not represent a common culture in the modern sense, rather it is a basic method for making stone tools that was shared across much of the Old World.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] In Europe, the more advanced Mousterian utilizing the Levallois technique appeared around 320,000 years ago, and had displaced the Acheulean in Europe and the Middle East by around 125,000 years ago.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] The Acheulean had also disappeared from Africa by this time.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] The Acheulean may have lasted much later, until around 50,000 years ago in East Asia.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] The Mode 1 industries created rough flake tools by hitting a suitable stone with a hammerstone.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] The resulting flake that broke off would have a natural sharp edge for cutting and could afterwards be sharpened further by striking another smaller flake from the edge if necessary (known as "retouch").
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] These early toolmakers may also have worked the stone they took the flake from (known as a core) to create chopper cores although there is some debate over whether these items were tools or just discarded cores.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] Advanced, later Acheulean toolmakers supplemented stone-on-stone percussion by utilizing "soft hammer" percussion using bone, antler, or wood tools.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] These type of hammers, compared to stone, yields more control over the shape of the finished tool, and can be used to resharpen blunted tools.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] The oldest locality showing evidence of "soft hammer" percussion in Eurasia is the Boxgrove site in southern England, dating to around 480,000 years ago.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] Soft hammer percussion may have emerged around the same time in Africa.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] Unlike the earlier Mode 1 industries, it was the core that was prized over the flakes that came from it.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] Another advance was that the Mode 2 tools were worked symmetrically and on both sides indicating greater care in the production of the final tool.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] Mode 3 technology emerged towards the end of Acheulean dominance and involved the Levallois technique, most famously exploited by the Mousterian industry.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] Transitional tool forms between the two are called Mousterian of Acheulean Tradition, or MTA types.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] The long blades of the Upper Palaeolithic Mode 4 industries appeared long after the Acheulean was abandoned.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] As the period of Acheulean tool use is so vast, efforts have been made to classify various stages of it such as John Wymer's division into Early Acheulean, Middle Acheulean, Late Middle Acheulean and Late Acheulean for material from Britain.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] These schemes are normally regional and their dating and interpretations vary.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] In Africa, there is a distinct difference in the tools made before and after 600,000 years ago with the older group being thicker and less symmetric and the younger being more extensively trimmed.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] The primary innovation associated with Acheulean hand-axes is that the stone was worked symmetrically and on both sides.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] For the latter reason, handaxes are, along with cleavers, bifacially worked tools that could be manufactured from the large flakes themselves or from prepared cores.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] Tool types found in Acheulean assemblages include pointed, cordate, ovate, ficron, and bout-coupé hand-axes (referring to the shapes of the final tool), cleavers, retouched flakes, scrapers, and segmental chopping tools.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] Materials used were determined by available local stone types; flint is most often associated with the tools but its use is concentrated in Western Europe; in Africa sedimentary and igneous rock such as mudstone and basalt were most widely used, for example.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] Other source materials include chalcedony, quartzite, andesite, sandstone, chert, and shale.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] Even relatively soft rock such as limestone could be exploited.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] In all cases the toolmakers worked their handaxes close to the source of their raw materials, suggesting that the Acheulean was a set of skills passed between individual groups.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] Some smaller tools were made from large flakes that had been struck from stone cores.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] These flake tools and the distinctive waste flakes produced in Acheulean tool manufacture suggest a more considered technique, one that required the toolmaker to think one or two steps ahead during work that necessitated a clear sequence of steps to create perhaps several tools in one sitting.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] A hard hammerstone would first be used to rough out the shape of the tool from the stone by removing large flakes.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] These large flakes might be re-used to create tools.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] The tool maker would work around the circumference of the remaining stone core, removing smaller flakes alternately from each face.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] The scar created by the removal of the preceding flake would provide a striking platform for the removal of the next.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] Misjudged blows or flaws in the material used could cause problems, but a skilled toolmaker could overcome them.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] Once the roughout shape was created, a further phase of flaking was undertaken to make the tool thinner.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] The thinning flakes were removed using a softer hammer, such as bone or antler.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] The softer hammer required more careful preparation of the striking platform and this would be abraded using a coarse stone to ensure the hammer did not slide off when struck.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] Final shaping was then applied to the usable cutting edge of the tool, again using fine removal of flakes.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] Some Acheulean tools were sharpened instead by the removal of a tranchet flake.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] This was struck from the lateral edge of the hand-axe close to the intended cutting area, resulting in the removal of a flake running along (parallel to) the blade of the axe to create a neat and very sharp working edge.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] This distinctive tranchet flake can be identified amongst flint-knapping debris at Acheulean sites.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] Loren Eiseley calculated that Acheulean tools have an average useful cutting edge of 20 centimetres (8 inches), making them much more efficient than the 5 centimetres (2 inches) average of Oldowan tools.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] A wear analysis of handaxes from the 480,000 year old late Acheulean Boxgrove site in England found that they were primarily if not exclusively used for animal butchery, with no evidence for their use in woodworking or digging.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] Alternative theories include a use for ovate hand-axes as a kind of hunting discus to be hurled at prey.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] Puzzlingly, there are also examples of sites where hundreds of hand-axes, many impractically large and also apparently unused, have been found in close association together.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] Sites such as Melka Kunturé in Ethiopia, Olorgesailie in Kenya, Isimila in Tanzania, and Kalambo Falls in Zambia have produced evidence that suggests Acheulean hand-axes might not always have had a functional purpose.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] Recently, it has been suggested that the Acheulean tool users adopted the handaxe as a social artifact, meaning that it embodied something beyond its function of a butchery or wood cutting tool.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] Knowing how to create and use these tools would have been a valuable skill and the more elaborate ones suggest that they played a role in their owners' identity and their interactions with others.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] This would help explain the apparent over-sophistication of some examples which may represent a "historically accrued social significance".
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] One theory goes further and suggests that some special hand-axes were made and displayed by males in search of a mate, using a large, well-made hand-axe to demonstrate that they possessed sufficient strength and skill to pass on to their offspring.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] Once they had attracted a female at a group gathering, it is suggested that they would discard their axes, perhaps explaining why so many are found together.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] This popular sexual selection hypothesis is controversial due to the assumptions made about sexual selection among extinct organisms.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] Stone knapping with limited digital dexterity makes the center of mass the required direction of flake removal.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] Physics then dictates a circular or oval end pattern, similar to the handaxe, for a leftover core after flake production.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] This would explain the abundance, wide distribution, proximity to source, consistent shape, and lack of actual use, of these artifacts.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] showing important sites of the Acheulean industry (clickable map).
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] The geographic distribution of Acheulean tools – and thus the peoples who made them – is often interpreted as being the result of palaeo-climatic and ecological factors, such as glaciation and the desertification of the Sahara Desert.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] Acheulean stone tools have been found across the continent of Africa, save for the dense rainforest around the Congo River which is not thought to have been colonized by hominids until later.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] It is thought that from Africa their use spread north and east to Asia: from Anatolia, through the Arabian Peninsula, across modern day Iran and Pakistan, and into India, and beyond.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] In Europe their users reached the Pannonian Basin and the western Mediterranean regions, modern day France, the Low Countries, western Germany, and southern and central Britain.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] Areas further north did not see human occupation until much later, due to glaciation.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] In Athirampakkam at Chennai in Tamil Nadu the Acheulean age started at 1.51 mya and it is also prior than North India and Europe.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] Until the 1980s, it was thought that the humans who arrived in East Asia abandoned the hand-axe technology of their ancestors and adopted chopper tools instead.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] An apparent division between Acheulean and non-Acheulean tool industries was identified by Hallam L.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] Movius, who drew the Movius Line across northern India to show where the traditions seemed to diverge.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] Later finds of Acheulean tools at Chongokni in South Korea and also in Mongolia and China, however, cast doubt on the reliability of Movius's distinction.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] Since then, a different division known as the Roe Line has been suggested.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] This runs across North Africa to Israel and thence to India, separating two different techniques used by Acheulean toolmakers.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] North and east of the Roe Line, Acheulean hand-axes were made directly from large stone nodules and cores; while, to the south and west, they were made from flakes struck from these nodules.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] Possible Acheulean-like bifacial technologies have also been discussed in relation to the Arubo 1 site in General Tinio, Nueva Ecija, Philippines, where archaeologists recovered a proto-handaxe and bifacial cleaver made from locally sourced chert.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] Pawlik noted that the proto-handaxe "would certainly be regarded as typical for the Early Acheulean" if found in regions traditionally associated with Acheulean industries.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] The assemblage has been cited in broader discussions regarding the diversity of bifacial technologies in Southeast Asia and the limitations of strict interpretations of the Movius Line.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] Most notably, however, it is *Homo ergaster* (sometimes called early *Homo erectus*), whose assemblages are almost exclusively Acheulean, who used the technique.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] Later, the related species *Homo heidelbergensis* (the common ancestor of both Neanderthals and *Homo sapiens*) used it extensively.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] Late Acheulean tools were still used by species derived from *H. erectus*, including *Homo sapiens idaltu* and early Neanderthals.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] The symmetry of the hand-axes has been used to suggest that Acheulean tool users possessed the ability to use language; the parts of the brain connected with fine control and movement are located in the same region that controls speech.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] The wider variety of tool types compared to earlier industries and their aesthetically as well as functionally pleasing form could indicate a higher intellectual level in Acheulean tool users than in earlier hominines.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] Others argue that there is no correlation between spatial abilities in tool making and linguistic behaviour, and that language is not learned or conceived in the same manner as artefact manufacture.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] Lower Palaeolithic finds made in association with Acheulean hand-axes, such as the Venus of Berekhat Ram, have been used to argue for artistic expression amongst the tool users.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] The incised elephant tibia from Bilzingsleben in Germany, and ochre finds from Kapthurin in Kenya and Duinefontein in South Africa, are sometimes cited as being some of the earliest examples of an aesthetic sensibility in human history.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] There are numerous other explanations put forward for the creation of these artefacts; however, evidence of human art did not become commonplace until around 50,000 years ago, after the emergence of modern *Homo sapiens*.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] The kill site at Boxgrove in England is another famous Acheulean site.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] Up until the 1970s these kill sites, often at waterholes where animals would gather to drink, were interpreted as being where Acheulean tool users killed game, butchered their carcasses, and then discarded the tools they had used.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] Since the advent of zooarchaeology, which has placed greater emphasis on studying animal bones from archaeological sites, this view has changed.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] Many of the animals at these kill sites have been found to have been killed by other predator animals, so it is likely that humans of the period supplemented hunting with scavenging from already dead animals.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] Excavations at the Bnot Ya'akov Bridge site, located along the Dead Sea rift in the southern Hula Valley of northern Israel, have revealed evidence of human habitation in the area from as early as 750,000 years ago.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] Archaeologists from the Hebrew University of Jerusalem claim that the site provides evidence of "advanced human behavior" half a million years earlier than has previously been estimated.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] Their report describes an Acheulean layer at the site in which numerous stone tools, animal bones, and plant remains have been found.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] Azykh cave located in Azerbaijan is another site where Acheulean tools were found.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] In 1968, a lower jaw of a new type of hominid was discovered in the fifth layer (so-called Acheulean layer) of the cave.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] Specialists named this type "Azykhantropus".
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] Only limited artefactual evidence survives of the users of Acheulean tools other than the stone tools themselves.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] Cave sites were exploited for habitation, but the hunter-gatherers of the Palaeolithic also possibly built shelters such as those identified in connection with Acheulean tools at Grotte du Lazaret and Terra Amata near Nice in France.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] The presence of the shelters is inferred from large rocks at the sites, which may have been used to weigh down the bottoms of tent-like structures or serve as foundations for huts or windbreaks.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] These stones may have been naturally deposited.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] In any case, a flimsy wood or animal skin structure would leave few archaeological traces after so much time.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] Fire was seemingly being exploited by *Homo ergaster*, and would have been a necessity in colonising colder Eurasia from Africa.
[src:mudbrick/acheulean] Conclusive evidence of mastery over it this early is, however, difficult to find.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] Adobe architecture has been dated to before 5,100 BP.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] Adobe bricks are rectangular prisms small enough that they can quickly air dry individually without cracking.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] They can be subsequently assembled, with the application of adobe mud to bond the individual bricks into a structure.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] There is no standard size, with substantial variations over the years and in different regions.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] In some areas a popular size measured 20 cm × 10 cm × 30 cm (8 by 4 by 12 inches) weighing about 10 kg (25 pounds); in other contexts the size is 25 cm × 10 cm × 36 cm (10 by 4 by 14 inches) weighing about 15 kg (35 pounds).
[src:mudbrick/adobe] The maximum sizes can reach up to 45 kg (100 pounds); above this weight it becomes difficult to move the pieces, and it is preferred to ram the mud *in situ*, resulting in a different typology known as rammed earth.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] In dry climates, adobe structures are extremely durable, and account for some of the oldest existing buildings in the world.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] Adobe buildings offer significant advantages due to their greater thermal mass, but they are known to be particularly susceptible to earthquake damage if they are not reinforced.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] Cases where adobe structures were widely damaged during earthquakes include the 1976 Guatemala earthquake, the 2003 Bam earthquake, and the 2010 Chile earthquake.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] Buildings made of sun-dried earth are common throughout the world (Middle East, Western Asia, North Africa, West Africa, South America, Southwestern North America, Southwestern and Eastern Europe.).
[src:mudbrick/adobe] Adobe had been in use by indigenous peoples of the Americas in the Southwestern United States, Mesoamerica, and the Andes for several thousand years.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] Puebloan peoples built their adobe structures with handsful or basketsful of adobe, until the Spanish introduced them to making bricks.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] Adobe bricks were used in Spain from the Late Bronze and Iron Ages (eighth century BCE onwards).
[src:mudbrick/adobe] Its wide use can be attributed to its simplicity of design and manufacture, and economics.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] The word *adobe* /əˈdoʊbiː/ has existed for around 4,000 years with relatively little change in either pronunciation or meaning.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] The word can be traced from the Middle Egyptian (c.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] 2000 BC) word *ḏbt* "mud brick" (with vowels unwritten).
[src:mudbrick/adobe] Middle Egyptian evolved into Late Egyptian and finally to Coptic (c.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] 600 BC), where it appeared as ⲧⲱⲃⲉ *tōbə*.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] This was adopted into Arabic as الطوب *aṭ-ṭawbu* or *aṭ-ṭūbu*, with the definite article *al-* attached to the root *tuba*.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] This was assimilated into the Old Spanish language as *adobe* [aˈdobe], probably via Mozarabic.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] English borrowed the word from Spanish in the early 18th century, still referring to mudbrick construction.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] In more modern English usage, the term *adobe* has come to include a style of architecture popular in the desert climates of North America, especially in New Mexico, regardless of the construction method.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] An adobe brick is a composite material made of earth mixed with water and an organic material such as straw or dung.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] The soil composition typically contains sand, silt, and clay.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] Straw is useful in binding the brick together and allowing the brick to dry evenly, thereby preventing cracking due to uneven shrinkage rates through the brick; dung offers the same advantage.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] The most desirable soil texture for producing the mud of adobe is 15% clay, 10–30% silt, and 55–75% fine sand.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] Another source quotes 15–25% clay and the remainder sand and coarser particles up to cobbles 50 to 250 mm (2 to 10 in), with no deleterious effect.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] Modern adobe is stabilized with either emulsified asphalt or Portland cement up to 10% by weight.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] No more than half the clay content should be expansive clays, with the remainder non-expansive illite or kaolinite.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] Too much expansive clay results in uneven drying through the brick, resulting in cracking, while too much kaolinite will make a weak brick.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] Typically the soils of the Southwest United States, where such construction has been widely used, are an adequate composition.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] Adobe walls are load bearing, meaning that they carry their own weight into the foundation rather than through another structure, hence the adobe must have sufficient compressive strength.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] In the United States, most building codes call for a minimum compressive strength of 2.1 N/mm2 (300 lbf/in2) for the adobe block.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] Adobe construction should be designed so as to avoid lateral structural loads that would cause bending loads.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] The building codes require the building sustain a 1 gram (0.035 oz) lateral acceleration earthquake load.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] Such an acceleration will cause lateral loads on the walls, resulting in shear and bending and inducing tensile stresses.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] To withstand such loads, the codes typically call for a tensile modulus of rupture strength of at least 2.1 N/mm2 (300 lbf/in2) for the finished block.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] In addition to being an inexpensive material with a small resource cost, adobe can serve as a significant heat reservoir due to the thermal properties inherent in the massive walls typical in adobe construction.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] In climates typified by hot days and cool nights, the high thermal mass of adobe mediates the high and low temperatures of the day, moderating the temperature of the living space.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] The massive walls require a large and relatively long input of heat from the sun (radiation) and from the surrounding air (convection) before they warm through to the interior.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] After the sun sets and the temperature drops, the warm wall will continue to transfer heat to the interior for several hours due to the time-lag effect.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] Thus, a well-planned adobe wall of appropriate thickness is very effective at controlling inside temperature through the wide daily fluctuations typical of desert climates, a factor which has contributed to its longevity as a building material.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] Thermodynamic material properties have significant variation in the literature.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] Some experiments suggest that the standard consideration of conductivity is not adequate for this material, as its main thermodynamic property is inertia, and conclude that experimental tests should be performed over a longer period of time than usual – preferably with changing thermal jumps.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] There is an effective R-value for a north facing 10-inch (25 cm) wall of R0=10 hr ft2 °F/Btu, which corresponds to thermal conductivity k=10 in x 1 ft/12 in /R0=0.33 Btu/(hr ft °F) or 0.57 W/(m K) in agreement with the thermal conductivity reported from another source.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] To determine the total R-value of a wall, scale R0 by the thickness of the wall in inches.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] The thermal resistance of adobe is also stated as an R-value for a 10-inch (25 cm) wall R0=4.1 hr ft2 °F/Btu.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] Another source provides the following properties: conductivity 0.30 Btu/(hr ft °F) or 0.52 W/(m K); specific heat capacity 0.24 Btu/(lb °F) or 1 kJ/(kg K) and density 106 lb/cu ft (1,700 kg/m3), giving heat capacity 25.4 Btu/(ft3 °F) or 1700 kJ/(m3 K).
[src:mudbrick/adobe] Using the average value of the thermal conductivity as k = 32 Btu/(hr ft °F) or 0.55 W/(m K), the thermal diffusivity is calculated to be 0.013 sq ft/h (3.4×10−7 m2/s).
[src:mudbrick/adobe] Poured and puddled adobe (puddled clay, piled earth), today called *cob*, is made by placing soft adobe in layers, rather than by making individual dried bricks or using a form.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] "Puddle" is a general term for a clay or clay and sand-based material worked into a dense, plastic state.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] These are the oldest methods of building with adobe in the Americas until holes in the ground were used as forms, and later wooden forms used to make individual bricks were introduced by the Spanish.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] Bricks made from adobe are usually made by pressing the mud mixture into an open timber frame.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] In North America, the brick is typically about 25 by 36 cm (10 by 14 in) in size.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] The mixture is molded into the frame, which is removed after initial setting.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] After drying for a few hours, the bricks are turned on edge to finish drying.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] The same mixture, without straw, is used to make mortar and often plaster on interior and exterior walls.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] Some cultures used lime-based cement for the plaster to protect against rain damage.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] Depending on the form into which the mixture is pressed, adobe can encompass nearly any shape or size, provided drying is even and the mixture includes reinforcement for larger bricks.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] Reinforcement can include manure, straw, cement, rebar, or wooden posts.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] Straw, cement, or manure added to a standard adobe mixture can produce a stronger, more crack-resistant brick.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] A test is done on the soil content first.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] To do so, a sample of the soil is mixed into a clear container with some water, creating an almost completely saturated liquid.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] The container is shaken vigorously for one minute.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] It is then allowed to settle for a day until the soil has settled into layers.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] Heavier particles settle out first, sand above, silt above that, and very fine clay and organic matter will stay in suspension for days.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] After the water has cleared, percentages of the various particles can be determined.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] Fifty to 60 percent sand and 35 to 40 percent clay will yield strong bricks.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] The Cooperative State Research, Education, and Extension Service at New Mexico State University recommends a mix of not more than 1⁄3 clay, not less than 1⁄2 sand, and never more than 1⁄3 silt.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] During the Great Depression, designer and builder Hugh W.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] Comstock used cheaper materials and made a specialized adobe brick called "Bitudobe." His first adobe house was built in 1936.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] The ground supporting an adobe structure should be compressed, as the weight of an adobe wall is significant and foundation settling may cause cracking of the wall.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] Footing depth is to be below the ground frost level.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] The footing and stem wall are commonly 60 and 35 cm (24 and 14 inches) thick, respectively.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] Modern construction codes call for the use of reinforcing steel in the footing and stem wall.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] Adobe walls usually never rise above two stories as they are load bearing and adobe has low structural strength.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] When creating window and door openings, a lintel is placed on top of the opening to support the bricks above.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] Atop the last courses of brick, bond beams made of heavy wood beams or modern reinforced concrete are laid to provide a horizontal bearing plate for the roof beams and to redistribute lateral earthquake loads to shear walls more able to carry the forces.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] To protect the interior and exterior adobe walls, finishes such as mud plaster, whitewash, or stucco can be applied.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] These protect the adobe wall from water damage, but need to be reapplied periodically.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] Alternatively, the walls can be finished with other nontraditional plasters that provide longer protection.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] Bricks made with stabilized adobe generally do not need protection of plasters.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] The traditional adobe roof has been constructed using a mixture of soil/clay, water, sand and organic materials.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] The mixture was then formed and pressed into wood forms, producing rows of dried earth bricks that would then be laid across a support structure of wood and plastered into place with more adobe.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] Depending on the materials available, a roof may be assembled using wood or metal beams to create a framework to begin layering adobe bricks.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] Depending on the thickness of the adobe bricks, the framework has been preformed using a steel framing and a layering of a metal fencing or wiring over the framework to allow an even load as masses of adobe are spread across the metal fencing like cob and allowed to air dry accordingly.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] This method was demonstrated with an adobe blend heavily impregnated with cement to allow even drying and prevent cracking.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] The more traditional flat adobe roofs are functional only in dry climates that are not exposed to snow loads.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] The heaviest wooden beams, called vigas, lie atop the wall.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] Across the vigas lie smaller members called latillas and upon those brush is then laid.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] To construct a flat adobe roof, beams of wood were laid to span the building, the ends of which were attached to the tops of the walls.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] Once the vigas, latillas and brush are laid, adobe bricks are placed.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] An adobe roof is often laid with bricks slightly larger in width to ensure a greater expanse is covered when placing the bricks onto the roof.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] Following each individual brick should be a layer of adobe mortar, recommended to be at least 25 mm (1 in) thick to make certain there is ample strength between the brick's edges and also to provide a relative moisture barrier during rain.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] Roof design evolved around 1850 in the American Southwest.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] Three inches (8 cm) of adobe mud was applied on top of the latillas, then 18 inches (45 cm) of dry adobe dirt applied to the roof.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] The dirt was contoured into a low slope to a downspout aka a 'canal'.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] When moisture was applied to the roof the clay particles expanded to create a waterproof membrane.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] Once a year it was necessary to pull the weeds from the roof and re-slope the dirt as needed.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] Depending on the materials, adobe roofs can be inherently fire-proof.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] The construction of a chimney can greatly influence the construction of the roof supports, creating an extra need for care in choosing the materials.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] The builders can make an adobe chimney by stacking simple adobe bricks in a similar fashion as the surrounding walls.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] In 1927, the Uniform Building Code (UBC) was adopted in the United States.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] Local ordinances, referencing the UBC added requirements to building with adobe.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] These included: restriction of building height of adobe structures to 1-story, requirements for adobe mix (compressive and shear strength) and new requirements which stated that every building shall be designed to withstand seismic activity, specifically lateral forces.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] By the 1980s however, seismic related changes in the California Building Code effectively ended solid wall adobe construction in California; however Post-and-Beam adobe and veneers are still being used.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] The largest structure ever made from adobe is the Arg-é Bam built by the Achaemenid Empire.
[src:mudbrick/adobe] Other large adobe structures are the Huaca del Sol in Peru, with 100 million signed bricks and the *ciudellas* of Chan Chan and Tambo Colorado, both in Peru.
[src:mudbrick/adze] An **adze** (/ædz/) or **adz** is an ancient and versatile cutting tool similar to an axe but with the cutting edge perpendicular to the handle rather than parallel.
[src:mudbrick/adze] Adzes have been used since the Stone Age.
[src:mudbrick/adze] They are used for smoothing or carving wood in hand woodworking, and as a hoe for agriculture and horticulture.
[src:mudbrick/adze] Two basic forms of an adze are the hand adze (short hoe)—a short-handled tool swung with one hand—and the foot adze (hoe)—a long-handled tool capable of powerful swings using both hands, the cutting edge usually striking at foot or shin level.
[src:mudbrick/adze] A similar tool is called a mattock, which differs by having two blades, one perpendicular to the handle and one parallel.
[src:mudbrick/adze] The adze is depicted in ancient Egyptian art from the Old Kingdom onward.
[src:mudbrick/adze] Originally the adze blades were made of stone, but already in the Predynastic Period copper adzes had all but replaced those made of flint.
[src:mudbrick/adze] Stone blades were fastened to the handle by tying and early bronze blades continued this simple construction.
[src:mudbrick/adze] It was not until the later Bronze Age that the handle passes through an eye at the top of the blade.
[src:mudbrick/adze] Examples of Egyptian adzes can be found in museums and on the Petrie Museum website.
[src:mudbrick/adze] The *ahnetjer* (Manuel de Codage transliteration: *aH-nTr*) depicted as an adze-like instrument, was used in the Opening of the Mouth ceremony, intended to convey power over their senses to statues and mummies.
[src:mudbrick/adze] It was apparently the foreleg of a freshly sacrificed bull or cow with which the mouth was touched.
[src:mudbrick/adze] As Iron Age technology moved south into Africa with migrating ancient Egyptians, they carried their technology with them, including adzes.
[src:mudbrick/adze] To this day, iron adzes are used all over rural Africa for various purposes—from digging pit latrines, and chopping firewood, to tilling crop fields—whether they are of maize (corn), coffee, tea, pyrethrum, beans, millet, yams, or a plethora of other cash and subsistence crops.
[src:mudbrick/adze] Prehistoric Māori adzes from New Zealand were for wood carving, typically made from pounamu sourced from the South Island.
[src:mudbrick/adze] During the Māori Archaic period found on the North Island were commonly made from greywacke from Motutapu Island or basalt from Opito Bay in the Coromandel, similar to adzes constructed on other Pacific Islands.
[src:mudbrick/adze] Early period notched adzes found in Northland were primarily made of argillite quarried from locations around the Marlborough and Nelson regions.
[src:mudbrick/adze] At the same time on Henderson Island, a small coral island in eastern Polynesia lacking any rock other than limestone, native populations may have fashioned giant clamshells into adzes.
[src:mudbrick/adze] American Northwest coast native peoples traditionally used adzes for both functional construction (from bowls to canoes) and art (from masks to totem poles).
[src:mudbrick/adze] Northwest coast adzes take two forms: hafted and D-handle.
[src:mudbrick/adze] The hafted form is similar in form to a European adze with the haft constructed from a natural crooked branch which approximately forms a 60% angle.
[src:mudbrick/adze] The thin end is used as the handle and the thick end is flattened and notched such that an adze iron can be lashed to it.
[src:mudbrick/adze] Modern hafts are sometimes constructed from a sawed blank with a dowel added for strength at the crook.
[src:mudbrick/adze] The second form is the D-handle adze which is basically an adze iron with a directly attached handle.
[src:mudbrick/adze] The D-handle, therefore, provides no mechanical leverage.
[src:mudbrick/adze] Northwest coast adzes are often classified by size and iron shape vs. role.
[src:mudbrick/adze] As with European adzes, iron shapes include straight, gutter and lipped.
[src:mudbrick/adze] Where larger Northwest adzes are similar in size to their European counterparts, the smaller sizes are typically much lighter such that they can be used for the detailed smoothing, shaping and surface texturing required for figure carving.
[src:mudbrick/adze] Final surfacing is sometimes performed with a crooked knife.
[src:mudbrick/adze] Ground stone adzes used to be produced by a variety of people in Western New Guinea (Indonesia), Papua New Guinea and some of the smaller Islands of Melanesia and Micronesia.
[src:mudbrick/adze] The hardstone would have been ground on a riverine rock with the help of water until the desired shape was obtained.
[src:mudbrick/adze] It was then fixed to a natural grown angled wood with resin and plant fibers.
[src:mudbrick/adze] Imported steel axes or machetes have now entirely replaced these tools for decades in even the remotest parts of New Guinea.
[src:mudbrick/adze] Indeed, even before the first foreign missionaries or colonial officials arrived in the New Guinea Highlands, inhabitants had already obtained steel tools through trade with their neighbors.
[src:mudbrick/adze] Stone tools are sometimes manufactured to be sold as curios to tourists.
[src:mudbrick/adze] Modern adzes are made from steel with wooden handles, and enjoy limited use: occasionally in semi-industrial areas, but particularly by "revivalists" such as those at the Colonial Williamsburg cultural center in Virginia, United States.
[src:mudbrick/adze] However, the traditional adze has largely been replaced by the sawmill and the powered plane, at least in industrialised cultures.
[src:mudbrick/adze] It remains in use for some specialist crafts, for example by coopers.
[src:mudbrick/adze] Adzes are also in current use by artists such as Northwest Coast American and Canadian Indigenous sculptors doing totem pole carving, as well as masks and bowls.
[src:mudbrick/adze] "Adzes are used for removing heavy waste, leveling, shaping, or trimming the surfaces of timber" and boards.
[src:mudbrick/adze] Generally, the user stands astride a board or log and swings the adze downwards between his feet, chipping off pieces of wood, moving backwards as they go and leaving a relatively smooth surface behind.
[src:mudbrick/adze] Foot adzes are most commonly known as shipbuilder's or carpenter's adzes.
[src:mudbrick/adze] On the modern, steel adze the cutting edge may be flat for smoothing work to very rounded for hollowing work such as bowls, gutters and canoes.
[src:mudbrick/adze] The shoulders or sides of an adze may be curved called a *lipped adze*, used for notching.
[src:mudbrick/adze] The end away from the cutting edge is called the pole and be of different shapes, generally flat or a *pin pole*.
[src:mudbrick/adze] There are a number of specialist, short-handled adzes used by coopers, wainwrights, and chair makers, and in bowl and trough making.
[src:mudbrick/adze] Many of these have shorter handles for control and more curve in the head to allow better clearance for shorter cuts.
[src:mudbrick/adze] During the communist period of Bulgaria, a new multi-use woodworking adze, called Теслà (*Teslà*), emerged.
[src:mudbrick/adze] It has a sharpened edge perpendicular to the handle, resembling an adze, but it is also used like a carpenter's hammer.
[src:mudbrick/adze] On the back of the head is a textured poll for driving nails, and on the front is a V-shaped hole used for prying, to extract the bent nails.
[src:mudbrick/adze] There is a popular Bulgarian folk song called "На теслата дръжката" (eng: The tesla's handle) about a craftsman and the masculinity of his tool.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Africa straddles the equator and the prime meridian.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] The continent is surrounded by the Mediterranean Sea to the north, the Arabian plate and the Gulf of Aqaba to the northeast, the Indian Ocean to the southeast and the Atlantic Ocean to the west.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] France, Italy, Portugal, Spain, and Yemen have parts of their territories located on African geographical soil, mostly in the form of islands.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] The continent includes Madagascar and various archipelagos.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] It contains 54 fully recognised sovereign states, eight cities and islands that are part of non-African states, and two *de facto* independent states with limited or no recognition.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] This count does not include Malta and Sicily, which are geologically part of the African continent.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Algeria is Africa's largest country by area, and Nigeria is its largest by population.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] African nations cooperate through the establishment of the African Union, which is headquartered in Addis Ababa.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Africa is highly biodiverse; it is the continent with the largest number of megafauna species, as it was least affected by the extinction of the Pleistocene megafauna.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] However, Africa is also heavily affected by a wide range of environmental issues, including desertification, deforestation, water scarcity, and pollution.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] These entrenched environmental concerns are expected to worsen as climate change impacts Africa.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] The UN Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change has identified Africa as the continent most vulnerable to climate change.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] The history of Africa is long, complex, and varied, and has often been under-appreciated by the global historical community.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] In African societies the oral word is revered, and they have generally recorded their history via oral tradition, which has led anthropologists to term them "oral civilisations", contrasted with "literate civilisations" which pride the written word.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] African culture is rich and diverse both within and between the continent's regions, encompassing art, cuisine, music and dance, religion, and dress.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Africa, particularly Eastern Africa, is widely accepted to be the place of origin of humans and the Hominidae clade, also known as the great apes.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] The earliest hominids and their ancestors have been dated to around 7 million years ago, and *Homo sapiens* (modern human) are believed to have originated in Africa 350,000 to 260,000 years ago.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Throughout history the continent saw the rise and fall of many kingdoms and empires, such as Ancient Egypt, Makuria, the Fatimids, Mali, the Asante, Kongo, the Luba, Bunyoro, Great Zimbabwe, Imerina, and the Zulu.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Despite the predominance of states, many societies were heterarchical and stateless.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Slave trades created various diasporas, especially in the Americas.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] From the late-19th century to early 20th century, driven by the Second Industrial Revolution, most of Africa was rapidly conquered and colonised by European nations, save for Ethiopia and Liberia.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] European rule had significant impacts on Africa's societies, and colonies were maintained for the purpose of economic exploitation and extraction of natural resources.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Most present states emerged from a process of decolonisation following World War II, and established the Organisation of African Unity in 1963, the predecessor to the African Union.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] The nascent countries decided to keep their colonial borders, with traditional power structures used in governance to varying degrees.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Under Roman rule, Carthage became the capital of the province then named *Africa Proconsularis*, following the Roman victory over the Carthaginians in the Third Punic War in 146 BC, which also included the coastal part of modern Libya.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] The Latin suffix *-ica* can sometimes be used to denote a land (e.g., in *Celtica* from *Celtae*, as used by Julius Caesar).
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] The later Muslim region of Ifriqiya, following its conquest of the Byzantine (Eastern Roman) Empire's *Exarchatus Africae*, also preserved a form of the name.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] According to the Romans, Africa lies to the west of Egypt, while "Asia" was used to refer to Anatolia and lands to the east.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] A definite line was drawn between the two continents by the geographer Ptolemy (85–165 CE), indicating Alexandria along the Prime Meridian and making the isthmus of Suez and the Red Sea the boundary between Asia and Africa.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] As Europeans came to understand the real extent of the continent, the idea of "Africa" expanded with their knowledge.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] In accordance with African cosmology, African historical consciousness viewed historical change and continuity, order and purpose within the framework of man and his environment, the gods, and his ancestors, and he believed himself part of a holistic spiritual entity.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] In African societies, the historical process is largely a communal one, with eyewitness accounts, hearsay, reminiscences, and occasionally visions, dreams, and hallucinations crafted into narrative oral traditions which are performed and transmitted through generations.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] In oral traditions time is sometimes mythical and social, and ancestors were considered historical actors.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Mind and memory shapes traditions, as events are condensed over time and crystallise into clichés.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Oral tradition can be exoteric or esoteric.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] It speaks to people according to their understanding, unveiling itself in accordance with their aptitudes.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Africa is considered by most paleoanthropologists to be the oldest inhabited territory on Earth, with the Human species originating from the continent.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] During the mid-20th century, anthropologists discovered many fossils and evidence of human occupation perhaps as early as seven million years ago ("Before Present"; BP).
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Fossil remains of several species of early apelike humans thought to have evolved into modern humans, such as *Australopithecus afarensis* radiometrically dated to approximately 3.9–3.0 million years BP, *Paranthropus boisei* (c.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] 2.3–1.4 million years BP) and *Homo ergaster* (c.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] 1.9 million–600,000 years BP) have been discovered.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] After the evolution of *Homo sapiens* approximately 350,000 to 260,000 years BP in Africa, the continent was mainly populated by groups of hunter-gatherers.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] These first modern humans left Africa and populated the rest of the globe during the Out of Africa II migration dated to approximately 50,000 years BP, exiting the continent either across Bab-el-Mandeb over the Red Sea, the Strait of Gibraltar in Morocco, or the Isthmus of Suez in Egypt.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Other migrations of modern humans within the African continent have been dated to that time, with evidence of early human settlement found in Southern Africa, Southeast Africa, North Africa, and the Sahara.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] However, the warming and drying climate meant that by 5,000 BC, the Sahara region was becoming increasingly dry and hostile.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Around 3500 BC, due to a tilt in the Earth's orbit, the Sahara experienced a period of rapid desertification.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] The domestication of cattle in Africa preceded agriculture and seems to have existed alongside hunter-gatherer cultures.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] It is speculated that by 6,000 BC, cattle were domesticated in North Africa.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] In West Africa, a wet phase ushered in an expanding rainforest and wooded savanna from Senegal to Cameroon.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Between 9,000 and 5,000 BC, Niger–Congo speakers domesticated the oil palm and raffia palm.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Black-eyed peas and voandzeia (African groundnuts), were domesticated, followed by okra and kola nuts.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Since most of the plants grew in the forest, the Niger–Congo speakers invented polished stone axes for clearing forest.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Pygmies are thought to have inhabited Central Africa for many millennia, splitting into eastern and western groups around 5,000 BP.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Over 150,000 BP, there was an early dispersal of anatomically modern humans to Southern Africa, equated with the modern-day Khoisan who have preserved their traditional hunter-gatherer way of life.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] From 3500 BC, nomes (ruled by nomarchs) coalesced to form the kingdoms of Lower Egypt and Upper Egypt in northeast Africa.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Around 3100 BC Upper Egypt conquered Lower Egypt to unify Egypt under the 1st dynasty, with the process of consolidation and assimilation completed by the time of the 3rd dynasty who formed the Old Kingdom of Egypt in 2686 BC.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] The Kingdom of Kerma emerged around this time to become the dominant force in Nubia, controlling territory as large as Egypt between the 1st and 4th cataracts of the Nile.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] The height of the Old Kingdom saw the construction of many great pyramids, though under the 6th dynasty power gradually decentralised to the nomarchs, culminating in the disintegration of the kingdom, exacerbated by drought and famine.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Around 2055 BC, the 11th dynasty, based in Thebes, conquered the others to form the Middle Kingdom of Egypt, and the 12th dynasty expanded into Lower Nubia at the expense of Kerma.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Around 1700 BC, the Middle Kingdom fractured in two, and the Hyksos (a militaristic people from Palestine) invaded and conquered Lower Egypt, while Kerma coordinated invasions deep into Egypt to reach its greatest extent.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] In 1550 BC, the 18th dynasty expelled the Hyksos, and established the New Kingdom of Egypt.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] The New Kingdom conquered the Levant from the Canaanites, Mittani, Amorites, and Hittites, and extinguished Kerma, incorporating Nubia into the empire, and sending the Egyptian empire into its golden age.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Internal struggles, drought, famine, and invasions by a confederation of seafaring peoples contributed to the New Kingdom's collapse in 1069 BC.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] The New Kingdom's collapse liberated the Kingdom of Kush in Nubia, which manoeuvred into power in Upper Egypt and conquered Lower Egypt in 754 BC to form the Kushite Empire.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] The Kushites ruled for a century and oversaw a revival in pyramid building, until they were driven out of Egypt by the Assyrians in 663 BC in reprisal for their expansion towards the Assyrian Empire.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] The Assyrians installed a puppet dynasty that later gained independence and once more unified Egypt, until it was conquered by the Achaemenid Empire in 525 BC.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Egypt briefly regained independence from the Achaemenids under the 28th dynasty from 404 to 343 BC.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] The conquest of Achaemenid Egypt by Alexander the Great in 332 BC marked the beginning of Hellenistic rule and the installation of the Macedonian Ptolemaic dynasty in Egypt.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] The Ptolemaics lost their holdings outside of Africa to the Seleucids in the Syrian Wars, expanded into Cyrenaica, and briefly occupied part of Kush in the 3rd century BC.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] In the 1st century BC, Ptolemaic Egypt became entangled in a Roman civil war, leading to its conquest by the Romans in 30 BC.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Kush persisted as a major regional power until, having been weakened from internal rebellion amid worsening climatic conditions, invasions by Aksum and the Noba caused their disintegration into Makuria, Alodia, and Nobatia around the 5th century AD.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] In the Horn of Africa, there was the Land of Punt, a kingdom on the Red Sea which was a close trading partner of Ancient Egypt in the 3rd and 2nd millennia BC.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Rodolfo Fattovich equated it to the Gash Group in the Sudanese-Eritrean lowlands, and some scholars have hypothesised modern-day Somalia, while Kenneth Kitchen and Felix Chami locate it on Zanzibar Island.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] In the Eritrean-Ethiopian Highlands, the kingdom of dʿmt rose c.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] 980 BC as the region was incorporated into global trading networks, and it exhibited Sabaean influences which most scholars attribute to a small migration of Sabaeans and their assimilation.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Several scholars consider there to have been other contemporaneous states, and dʿmt's collapse in the mid-1st century BC saw the region inhabited by small polities.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Modern-day Somalia was inhabited by nomadic pastoralists, and along the Horn's coast there were many ancient Somali city-states that thrived off of the wider Red Sea trade, and enjoyed a lucrative monopoly on cinnamon from Ancient India due to their freedom from Roman interference.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] In the 1st century AD, the Kingdom of Aksum rose from a city-state to rule much of the northern Ethiopian-Eritrean Highlands and the Red Sea port of Adulis.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Aksum was described as one of the four great powers by Persian prophet Mani in the 3rd century.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Aksum's king converted from traditional religion to Christianity in the 4th century, gradually followed by the population.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] In the 6th century, Aksum conquered South Arabia, though struggled to maintain control over it, and began to gradually lose its dominance over Red Sea trade to Persians and Arabs.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Northwest Africa (the Maghreb) was inhabited by Berber semi-nomadic pastoralists.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] In the 1st millennium BC, Phoenician migration and settlement came in search for precious metals in the Gulf of Tunis.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] This grew into Ancient Carthage after gaining independence from Phoenicia in the 6th century BC, and they built an extensive trading empire with a strict mercantile network.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Carthage's collapse and conquest by Rome in the Punic Wars (3rd and 2nd centuries BC) saw Numidia and Mauretania become major powers in the Maghreb.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Towards the end of the 2nd century BC Mauretania fought alongside Numidia's Jugurtha against the Romans in the Jugurthine War after he had usurped the Numidian throne from a Roman ally.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Together they inflicted heavy casualties, with the war only ending inconclusively when Mauretania's Bocchus I sold out Jugurtha to the Romans.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Around the turn of the millennium, both came under direct Roman rule.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] While traditional religion predominated among Berbers, some people converted to Christianity.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] In the 5th century AD the Vandals conquered Roman Africa before the fall of Rome, though the province was reconquered by the Byzantines a century later.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Large swathes of indigenous peoples regained self-governance in Masuna and its numerous successor polities in the Maghreb, including the kingdoms of Ouarsenis, Aurès, and Altava.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] In the western Sahel the rise of settled communities occurred largely as a result of the domestication of millet and of sorghum, and cattle pastoralism began c.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Extensive east-west belts of deserts, grasslands, and forests from north to south were crucial for the moulding of their respective societies and meant that symbiotic trade relations developed in response to the differing environments.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Beginning around 4000 BC, the Tichitt culture in modern-day Mauritania and Mali is the oldest known complexly organised society in West Africa, while others included the Kintampo culture in modern-day Ghana, the Nok culture in modern-day Nigeria, and the Daima culture around Lake Chad.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Towards the end of the 3rd century AD, a wet period in the Sahel created areas for human habitation and exploitation that had not been habitable for the best part of a millennium.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] The Ghana Empire (also called *Wagadu*) rose out of the Tichitt culture, growing wealthy following the introduction of the camel to the western Sahel, which revolutionised the trans-Saharan trade that linked their capital and Aoudaghost with Tahert and Sijilmasa in North Africa.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Soninke tradition holds that the final founding of Wagadu occurred after Dinga did a deal with Bida, a serpent deity who was guarding a well, to sacrifice one maiden a year in exchange for assurance regarding plenty of rainfall and gold supply.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Based on large tumuli scattered across West Africa dating to this period, several scholars have speculated that there were further simultaneous and preceding states relative to Wagadu.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] In the Grasslands of northwestern Cameroon, Bantu-speaking agriculturalists started to gradually migrate south sometime between 5000 BC and 3000 BC.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Despite intensive research, the cause of the migrations, and that of the directions taken, is still unclear, however there is consensus that there were multiple dispersal events.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Around 1500 BC, Bantu speakers reached central Cameroon.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] The 'Western Stream' likely followed the coast and the major rivers of the Congo system southwards to reach the southern fringe of the Congolian Rainforest around 500 BC (some may have used the sea to circumvent the rainforest).
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Their arrival coincided with the spread of iron metallurgy through Central Africa.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Meanwhile, the 'Eastern Stream' travelled either the northern fringe of the rainforest or the Ubangi River eastwards, and reached just west of Lake Victoria around 500 BC.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] While there, Bantu speakers adopted iron metallurgy from Cushitic speakers already present, and coexisted with them.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Dispersal from the Great Lakes region occurred in two more streams.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] One went west to meet the Western Stream in the DR Congo and Angola, while the other went south and spread across Eastern and Southern Africa.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Around the turn of the millennium, Bantu speakers reached central modern-day Tanzania and near Dar es Salaam, before rapidly moving southwards along the coast to reach modern-day Kwazulu Natal in South Africa around the 3rd century AD.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Throughout this, Bantu speakers displaced, replaced, or intermarried with and absorbed hunter-gatherer and agricultural groups.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] In the 7th and 8th centuries, as part of the Arab conquests which sought to spread Islamic rule, the Rashidun and Umayyad caliphates conquered North Africa at the expense of the Byzantine Empire and Berber leaders such as Kusaila and Kahina.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Large numbers of Berber and Coptic people willingly converted to Islam, and followers of Abrahamic religions ('People of the Book') were protected, though followers of Berber traditional religion were violently oppressed.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] In the 8th century the Berber Revolt rocked the Caliphate and Berber dynasties took control over the Maghreb, while the Tulunids briefly controlled Egypt.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] In the 10th century, the Fatimids rose to power in modern-day Tunisia, established a rival caliphate, and conquered Egypt, before expanding into the Middle East.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] In the 11th century the Almoravids conquered the Maghreb and intervened in the Christian reconquest of Iberia.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Saladin, a Fatimid vizier, usurped power in the 12th century and established the Ayyubid dynasty which restored Egyptian prestige, while the Almohad revolution deposed the Almoravids to the east.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] After Christian gains in Iberia in the 13th century, the Almohads disintegrated into the Marinids, Zayyanids, and Hafsids in modern-day Morocco, Algeria, and Tunisia respectively.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] In the face of Mongol expansion, Mamluk generals seized power in Egypt and expanded into the Middle East.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] In the early-16th century, the Ottoman Empire rapidly conquered North Africa (save for Morocco, now under Saadi rule) to counter Spanish expansionism.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] In the following centuries, over a million Europeans are estimated to have been captured and enslaved by Barbary corsairs.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] The Ottoman regencies became more independent during the 18th century.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] In the central Sahel around Lake Chad, the Kanem–Bornu Empire ruled from the 6th century, and projected power over the Hausa Kingdoms.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] To the east during 7th century, Makuria conquered Nobatia to become the dominant power in the region and resisted Muslim expansion.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] They later entered a severe decline following civil war and Arab migrations to the Sudan and had disintegrated by the 15th century, giving rise to the Funj Sultanate.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] The Tunjur empire's collapse in the central Sudan saw the rise of the Bagirmi, Wadai, and Darfur sultanates, which frequently raided the populations to their south for slaves.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] In the Horn of Africa, Aksum lost control of the Red Sea, and its isolation from Christendom caused Ethiopian society to introspect and take inspiration from the Old Testament.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Islamised Beja invaded the Ethiopian Highlands, forcing Aksum to migrate south, where, according to tradition, Aksum's expansion was met by a Jewish or traditionalist queen who destroyed the state c.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] During the 13th century, hegemony in the Horn was contested by the Christian Zagwe, the Muslims of Shewa, and the traditionalist Damot; the Solomonic dynasty overthrew the Zagwe to found the Ethiopian Empire, while Shewa was replaced by Ifat.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Soon after, Ethiopia conquered Damot and the Muslim states, entering into a 'golden age'.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] In the 16th century Muslims united behind Adal in *jihad* to reconquer the Muslim lands and occupy Ethiopia, until, with Portuguese assistance, Ethiopia counter-attacked and its sovereignty was restored in a reduced state.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] The 16th and 17th centuries also saw Oromo invasions into the Horn, weakening Ethiopia further and causing the collapse of Adal, while Ajuran on the east coast also disintegrated.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Ethiopia briefly consolidated its authority in the late-17th century, though the turn of the century saw fragmentation and gradually-increasing anarchy, which continued throughout the 18th century.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] In the Sahel region of West Africa, the Ghana Empire formed from between the 2nd and 8th centuries, while from the 7th century the Gao Empire ruled to its east.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Almoravid capture of royal Aoudaghost led to Ghana's conversion to Islam in the 11th century, and climatic changes led to Ghana's conquest by its vassal Sosso in the 13th century.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Sosso was quickly overthrown by the Mali Empire who conquered Gao and dominated the trans-Saharan trade.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] The Mossi Kingdoms were established to its south.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] The 15th century saw the crumbling of the Mali Empire, with the dominant power in the region becoming the Songhai Empire centered on Gao.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Weakened by internal conflict, in 1591 Gao was conquered by Morocco, and the political vacuum came to be filled by the Segou Empire and several other states.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] The once lucrative trans-Saharan trade gradually lost its prominence to the coastal Atlantic trade with Europeans, and the following centuries saw many droughts, famines, and epidemics.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] In the forest regions of West Africa, various kingdoms and empires flourished, such as the Yoruba empires of Ife and Oyo, the Igbo Kingdom of Nri, the Edo Kingdom of Benin (famous for its art), the Dagomba Kingdom of Dagbon, and the Akan kingdoms of Bonoman and Adanse.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] They came into contact with the Portuguese in the 15th century which saw the start of the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] The Asante Empire was established in present-day Ghana.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Between 1515 and 1800, 8 million Africans were exported in the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] In the western Congo Basin by the 13th century there were three main confederations of states: the Seven Kingdoms, Mpemba, and one led by Vungu.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] In the 14th century the Kingdom of Kongo emerged and dominated the region, with the Tio Kingdom to its north and Mwene Muji to its northeast.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Over the course of the late-16th and 17th centuries, the Portuguese sought to conquer Ndongo (allied to Matamba) in the Angolan Wars; despite fierce resistance from Queen Nzinga, and brief occupation of Luanda by the Dutch (allied to Kongo), Portugal controlled most of Ndongo by the 1670s.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] The late-17th century saw Kongo fragment between royal houses as several vassals broke away; by the time of Kongo's restoration in 1709, it had ceased being the dominant regional power.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Also during the 17th century, in the textile-producing northeast, the Boma, Yaka, and possibly the Kuba and Pende kingdoms broke away from Mwene Muji.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] In the eastern Congo Basin, farmers, fishermen, and hunters (often Pygmies) built symbiotic relations.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Jan Vansina wrote that in the southern savanna 'lords of the land' held priestly roles due to their special relationship with the spirits of the land, and held sway over multiple villages, effectively ruling embryonic kingdoms.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Accordingly, as lineages grew, authority was opportunistically absorbed or incorporated by force.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] The centre of the Luba Empire is yet to undergo archaeological research, meaning knowledge about its rise is limited; its foundation is typically dated to the 14th/15th centuries, though scholarly estimates range from the 8th to 17th centuries.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] A Lunda state formed in the Nkalany Valley (estimates range from c.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] 1700), in the 18th century, Lunda rapidly expanded into an extensive commonwealth across the southern savanna, using the institutions of perpetual kinship and positional succession to incorporate peoples.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Meanwhile, Luba expanded its number of tributaries, in some cases using its widely acknowledged prestige to intervene in succession disputes and distribute ritually-powerful royal regalia related to *bulopwe* (sacred kingship), in other cases using conquest.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] In the northern Great Lakes, the Empire of Kitara rose around the 11th century, famed for its oral traditions.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Peter Robertshaw considered its rulers (the Chwezi) to have been religious leaders who utilised networks of hill-top shrines to project authority.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Around 1500, severe droughts and famine destabilised the region, occurring again during the early-17th and 18th centuries.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Luo-speaking peoples migrated from the Upper Nile basin into modern-day Uganda, and a Biito dynasty replaced the Chwezi in Bunyoro-Kitara.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Over the following centuries, the kingdoms of Bunyoro-Kitara, Buganda, and Rwanda struggled for hegemony among others.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Throughout the 16th and 17th centuries, Bunyoro raided states to the south such as Nkore and Rwanda.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Mpororo rose and fragmented during the 18th century, while Buganda rapidly expanded at the expense of Bunyoro to become the major power in the region.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] The East African interior was inhabited by pastoralist Cushitic and Nilotic speakers, along with Bantu speakers who continued to expand and adapt to their lands while absorbing the former two; the 17th century saw the establishment of tributary systems that stabilised the region.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] On the Swahili coast the Swahili city-states thrived off of the Indian Ocean trade and gradually Islamized, giving rise to the Kilwa Sultanate from the 10th century.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] In the 15th century, trade routes for Zimbabwean gold shifted north, weakening Kilwa.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] The Portuguese arrived at the coast soon after, and exploited divisions between coastal city-states to gain control over them while utilising a powerful navy.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] In the 17th and 18th centuries, Lamu-Swahili cities rebelled against the Portuguese and allied the Omani Empire which supplanted Portuguese rule.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Madagascar was settled by Austronesian peoples between the 5th and 7th centuries, as societies organized at the behest of *hasina* and competed over with one another over the island's estuaries and bridgeheads.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] From around the 15th century, southern Madagascar became integrated into global trade; the Sakalava Empire rose to dominate west-coastal trade, accompanied by numerous other states, and the island saw several failed European colonial ventures.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] In Southern Africa, an early kingdom was Mapungubwe, which collapsed c.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] 1300 as Great Zimbabwe, with its monumental dry-stone walls, rose to become the region's main political and economic centre.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Following shifting trade routes north to the Zambezi and unclear circumstances, Great Zimbabwe entered into decline and was succeeded by the Mutapa Empire and Kingdom of Butua in the 15th century.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Mutapa was briefly vassalised by the Portuguese in the 17th century, the latter-half of which saw widespread famine and disease, until Changamire Dombo revolted in the 1680s, conquered Butua to found the Rozvi Empire, and expelled all Portuguese from the Zimbabwean Plateau.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] North of the Zambezi, Maravi around Lake Malawi expanded in the 17th century, but the collapse of its succession system in the 18th century precipitated its disintegration.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] By the late-1st millennium CE, Bantu-speaking farmers populated most of Southern Africa's cultivable savannas, reaching southwards to the Kei River; they traded goods such as livestock, grain, and metal tools between communities and with hunter-gatherers.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Further south, the Dutch began colonizing the western Cape in the 17th century, and Britain seized control of the colony around the turn of the 19th century.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] In the late-18th century, the interplay of pre-existing trends of political centralization with the effects of international trade, environmental instability, and European colonisation set the *Mfecane* ("Crushing") in motion, as various African states were founded.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] By the turn of the 19th century, many of Africa's economic and political structures were unstable and brittle as a result of long-term effects of the slave trade.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] In Egypt Muhammad Ali led a national movement to seize power from Ottoman suzerainty, instituting sweeping reforms and greatly strengthening Egyptian power by militaristic expansion.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Meanwhile, in West Africa the Fula *jihad*s, which had been gaining momentum throughout the 18th century, culminated in the establishment of the expansive Sokoto and Hamdullahi caliphates.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] In the Horn, Ethiopia underwent reforms, seeking to revive the imperial state, something that was later achieved by Menelik II's conquests.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] In Southern Africa the *Mfecane* propelled large long-distance migrations that caused widespread disruption across the vast region, while several Boer republics were founded.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] European campaigns to abolish the Atlantic slave trade led to supply refocusing on internal markets and saw the rapid growth of the Indian Ocean slave trade.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Across the continent many rulers attempted reforms and indigenous forms of 'modernisation', however these efforts were consistently undermined by European traders and missionaries as the tide of European encroachment rose.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] For 400 years, European nations had mainly limited their involvement to trading stations on the African coast, with few daring to venture inland.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] The Industrial Revolution in Europe produced several technological innovations which assisted them in overcoming this 400-year pattern.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] One was the development of repeating rifles, which were easier and quicker to load than muskets.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Maxim developed the maxim gun, the model of the modern-day machine gun.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] European states kept these weapons largely among themselves by refusing to sell these weapons to African leaders.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] African germs took numerous European lives and deterred permanent settlements.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Diseases such as yellow fever, sleeping sickness, yaws, and leprosy made Africa a very inhospitable place for Europeans.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] The deadliest disease was malaria, endemic throughout Tropical Africa.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] In 1854, the discovery of quinine and other medical innovations helped to make conquest and colonisation in Africa possible.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] There were strong motives for the conquest of Africa.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Raw materials were needed for European factories, and free trade was championed to prevent Africans from regulating their economies.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Prestige and imperial rivalries were at play.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Acquiring African colonies would show rivals that a nation was powerful and significant.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] These contextual factors forged the Scramble for Africa; during the late-19th and early-20th centuries the European powers partitioned and conquered almost all of Africa despite fierce resistance (only Ethiopia and Liberia remained independent).
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Traditional leaders were incorporated into the colonial regimes as a form of indirect rule to extract human and natural resources and curb organized resistance.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Colonial borders were drawn unilaterally by the Europeans, often cutting across bonds of kinship, language, culture, and established routes, and sometimes incorporating groups who previously had little in common.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] The threat to trade routes was mitigated by poor policing and African entrepreneurs (viewed as smugglers) who exploited the differing tax and legal schemes.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] The first few decades of European colonialism saw intense violence, disorder, and atrocities, such as that of the Congo Free State, German South West Africa, and French Algeria, with the late colonial period relatively peaceful in comparison.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Colonial rule had wide-reaching effects on African societies, such as the spread of Christianity as part of the 'civilising mission'.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] African culture was strongly denigrated and persecuted, as pervasive racial discrimination deepened the scars of humiliation.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Imperial rule by Europeans continued until after the conclusion of World War II, when almost all remaining colonial territories gradually obtained formal independence.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Independence movements in Africa gained momentum following World War II, which left the major European powers weakened.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] In 1951, Libya, a former Italian colony, gained independence.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] In 1956, Tunisia and Morocco won their independence from France.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Ghana followed suit the next year (March 1957), becoming the first of the sub-Saharan colonies to be granted independence.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Over the next decade, waves of decolonisation took place across the continent, culminating in the 1960 Year of Africa and the establishment of the Organisation of African Unity in 1963.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Portugal's overseas presence in sub-Saharan Africa (most notably in Angola, Cape Verde, Mozambique, Guinea-Bissau, and São Tomé and Príncipe) lasted from the 16th century to 1975, after the Estado Novo regime was overthrown in a military coup in Lisbon.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Rhodesia unilaterally declared independence from the United Kingdom in 1965, under the white minority government of Ian Smith, but was not internationally recognised as an independent state (as Zimbabwe) until 1980, when black nationalists gained power after a bitter guerrilla war.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Although South Africa was one of the first African countries to gain independence, the state remained under the control of the country's white minority, initially through qualified voting rights and from 1956 by a system of racial segregation known as apartheid, until 1994.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] As of 2025, Africa contains 54 sovereign countries.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Since independence, African states have frequently been hampered by instability, corruption, violence, and authoritarianism.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] The vast majority of African states are republics that operate under some form of the presidential system of rule.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] However, few of them have been able to sustain democratic governments on a permanent basis—per the criteria laid out by Lührmann et al.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] (2018), only Botswana and Mauritius have been consistently democratic for the entirety of their post-colonial history.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Most African countries have experienced several coups or periods of military dictatorship.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Between 1990 and 2018, though, the continent as a whole has trended towards more democratic governance.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Upon independence an overwhelming majority of Africans lived in extreme poverty.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] The continent suffered from the lack of infrastructural or industrial development under colonial rule, along with political instability.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] With limited financial resources or access to global markets, relatively stable countries such as Kenya still experienced only very slow economic development.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Only a handful of African countries succeeded in obtaining rapid economic growth prior to 1990.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Exceptions include Libya and Equatorial Guinea, both of which possess large oil reserves.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Instability throughout the continent after decolonisation resulted primarily from marginalisation of ethnic groups, and corruption.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Faced with increasingly frequent and severe violence, military rule was widely accepted by the population of many countries as means to maintain order, and during the 1970s and 1980s a majority of African countries were controlled by military dictatorships.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Territorial disputes between nations and rebellions by groups seeking independence were also common in independent African states.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] The most devastating of these was the Nigerian Civil War, fought between government forces and an Igbo separatist republic, which resulted in a famine that killed 1–2 million people.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Two civil wars in Sudan, the first lasting from 1955 to 1972 and the second from 1983 to 2005, collectively killed around 3 million.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Both were fought primarily on ethnic and religious lines.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Cold War conflicts between the United States and the Soviet Union also contributed to instability.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Both the Soviet Union and the United States offered considerable incentives to African political and military leaders who aligned themselves with the superpowers' foreign policy.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] As an example, during the Angolan Civil War, the Soviet and Cuban aligned MPLA and the American aligned UNITA received the vast majority of their military and political support from these countries.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Many African countries became highly dependent on foreign aid.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] The sudden loss of both Soviet and American aid at the end of the Cold War and fall of the USSR resulted in severe economic and political turmoil in the countries most dependent on foreign support.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] There was a major famine in Ethiopia between 1983 and 1985, killing up to 1.2 million people, which most historians attribute primarily to the forced relocation of farmworkers and seizure of grain by the communist Derg government, further exacerbated by the civil war.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] In 1994 a genocide in Rwanda resulted in up to 800,000 deaths, added to a severe refugee crisis and fuelled the rise of militia groups in neighbouring countries.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] This contributed to the outbreak of the first and second Congo Wars, which were the most devastating military conflicts in modern Africa, with up to 5.5 million deaths, making it by far the deadliest conflict in modern African history and one of the costliest wars in human history.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Various conflicts between various insurgent groups and governments continue.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Since 2003, there has been an ongoing conflict in Darfur (Sudan), which peaked in intensity from 2003 to 2005 with notable spikes in violence in 2007 and 2013–15, killing around 300,000 people total.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] The Boko Haram Insurgency primarily within Nigeria (with considerable fighting in Niger, Chad, and Cameroon as well) has killed around 350,000 people since 2009.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Most African conflicts have been reduced to low-intensity conflicts as of 2022.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] However, the Tigray War from 2020 to 2022 killed an estimated 300,000–500,000 people, primarily due to famine.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Overall though, violence across Africa has greatly declined in the 21st century, with the end of civil wars in Angola, Sierra Leone, and Algeria in 2002, Liberia in 2003, and Sudan and Burundi in 2005.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] The Second Congo War, which involved 9 countries and several insurgent groups, ended in 2003.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] This decline in violence coincided with many countries abandoning communist-style command economies and opening up for market reforms, which over the course of the 1990s and 2000s promoted the establishment of permanent, peaceful trade between neighbouring countries (see Capitalist peace).
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Improved stability and economic reforms have led to a great increase in foreign investment into many African nations, mainly from China, which further spurred economic growth.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] Between 2000 and 2014, annual GDP growth in sub-Saharan Africa averaged 5.02%, doubling its total GDP from $811 billion to $1.63 trillion (constant 2015 USD).
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] North Africa experienced comparable growth rates.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] A significant part of this growth can also be attributed to the facilitated diffusion of information technologies and specifically the mobile telephone.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p01] While several individual countries have maintained high growth rates, since 2014 overall growth has considerably slowed, primarily as a result of falling commodity prices, continued lack of industrialisation, and epidemics such as Ebola and COVID-19.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Africa is the largest of the three great southward projections from the largest landmass of the Earth.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Separated from Europe by the Mediterranean Sea, it is joined to Asia at its northeast extremity by the Isthmus of Suez (transected by the Suez Canal), 163 km (101 mi) wide.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Geopolitically, Egypt's Sinai Peninsula east of the Suez Canal is often considered part of Africa as well.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] The coastline is 26,000 km (16,000 mi) long, and the absence of deep indentations of the shore is illustrated by the fact that Europe, which covers only 10,400,000 km2 (4,000,000 sq mi) – about a third of the surface of Africa – has a coastline of 32,000 km (20,000 mi).
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] From the most northerly point, Ras ben Sakka in Tunisia (37°21' N), to the most southerly point, Cape Agulhas in South Africa (34°51'15" S), is a distance of approximately 8,000 km (5,000 mi).
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Cape Verde, 17°33'22" W, the westernmost point, is a distance of approximately 7,400 km (4,600 mi) to Ras Hafun, 51°27'52" E, the most easterly projection that neighbours Cape Guardafui, the tip of the Horn of Africa.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Africa's largest country is Algeria, and its smallest country is Seychelles, an archipelago off the east coast.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] The smallest nation on the continental mainland is The Gambia.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] The African plate, also known as the Nubian plate, is a major tectonic plate that includes most of the continent of Africa (except for its easternmost part) and the adjacent oceanic crust to the west and south.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] It also includes a narrow strip of Western Asia along the Mediterranean Sea, including much of Israel, Palestine and Lebanon.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] It is bounded by the North American plate and South American plate to the west (separated by the Mid-Atlantic Ridge); the Arabian plate and Somali plate to the east; the Eurasian plate, Aegean Sea plate and Anatolian plate to the north; and the Antarctic plate to the south.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Between 60 million years ago and 10 million years ago, the Somali plate began rifting from the African plate along the East African Rift.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Since the continent of Africa consists of crust from both the African and the Somali plates, some literature refers to the African plate as the *Nubian plate* to distinguish it from the continent as a whole.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] The climate of Africa ranges from tropical to subarctic on its highest peaks.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Its northern half is primarily desert, or arid, while its central and southern areas contain both savanna plains and dense jungle (rainforest) regions.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] In between, there is a convergence, where vegetation patterns such as sahel and steppe dominate.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Africa is the hottest continent on Earth and 60% of the entire land surface consists of drylands and deserts.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] The record for the highest-ever recorded temperature, in Libya in 1922 (58 °C (136 °F)), was discredited in 2013.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Climate change in Africa is a serious threat because the continent is one of the most vulnerable regions to the effects of climate change, despite being responsible for less than 4% of global greenhouse emissions.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Climate change is causing increasingly erratic rainfall patterns, more frequent extreme weather events such as droughts, floods, and rising sea-surface temperatures across the continent.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] These changes threaten food and water security, biodiversity, public health, and economic development.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Africa is currently warming faster than the rest of the world on average.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Climate change intensifies existing socioeconomic vulnerabilities.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Large segments of the African population depend on climate-sensitive livelihoods such as agriculture (55 - 62% of the workforce in sub-Saharan Africa) and already live in poverty, heightening their exposure to shocks.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Health outcomes worsen as heat stress, vector-borne diseases (such as malaria and dengue), and malnutrition become more prevalent.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Over half (56%) of the over 2,000 recorded public health incidents in Africa between 2001 and 2021 were connected to climate change.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Resource scarcity contributes to displacement and conflict, particularly in fragile regions.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Urban areas, often characterized by informal settlements, face heightened risks from flooding and extreme heat.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Africa has over 3,000 protected areas, with 198 marine protected areas, 50 biosphere reserves, and 80 wetlands reserves.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Significant habitat destruction, increases in human population and poaching are reducing Africa's biological diversity and arable land.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Human encroachment, civil unrest and the introduction of non-native species threaten biodiversity in Africa.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] This has been exacerbated by administrative problems, inadequate personnel and funding problems.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Deforestation is affecting Africa at twice the world rate, according to the United Nations Environment Programme (UNEP).
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] The deforestation rate of 4.08 million hectares in 2000–2015 declined to 3.45 million ha per year in 2015–2025.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Some sources claim that approximately 90% of the original, virgin forests in West Africa have been destroyed.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Over 90% of Madagascar's original forests have been destroyed since the arrival of humans 2000 years ago.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] About 65% of Africa's agricultural land suffers from soil degradation.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] It is also home to a variety of "jungle" animals including snakes and primates and aquatic life such as crocodiles and amphibians.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] In addition, Africa has the largest number of megafauna species, as it was least affected by the extinction of the Pleistocene megafauna.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] African environmental problems are problems caused by the direct and indirect human impacts on the natural environment and affect humans and nearly all forms of life in Africa.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Issues include deforestation, soil degradation, air pollution, water pollution, coastal erosion, garbage pollution, climate change, Oil spills, Biodiversity loss, and water scarcity (resulting in problems with access to safe water supply and sanitation).
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] These issues result in environmental conflict and are connected to broader social struggles for democracy and sovereignty.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] The scarcity of climate adaptation techniques in Africa makes it the least resilient continent to climate change.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] The African Union (AU) is a continental union consisting of 55 member states.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] The union was formed, with Addis Ababa, Ethiopia, as its headquarters, on 26 June 2001.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] The union was officially established on 9 July 2002 as a successor to the Organisation of African Unity (OAU).
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] In July 2004, the African Union's Pan-African Parliament (PAP) was relocated to Midrand, in South Africa, but the African Commission on Human and Peoples' Rights remained in Addis Ababa.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] The African Union, not to be confused with the AU Commission, is formed by the Constitutive Act of the African Union, which aims to transform the African Economic Community, a federated commonwealth, into a state under established international conventions.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] The African Union has a parliamentary government, known as the African Union Government, consisting of legislative, judicial and executive organs.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] It is led by the African Union President and Head of State, who is also the President of the Pan-African Parliament.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] A person becomes AU President by being elected to the PAP, and subsequently gaining majority support in the PAP.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] The government of the AU consists of all-union, regional, state, and municipal authorities, as well as hundreds of institutions, that together manage the day-to-day affairs of the institution.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Extensive human rights abuses still occur in several parts of Africa, often under the oversight of the state.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Most of such violations occur for political reasons, often as a side effect of civil war.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Countries where major human rights violations have been reported in recent times include the Democratic Republic of the Congo, Sierra Leone, Liberia, Sudan, Zimbabwe, and Ivory Coast.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] African nations have made great efforts to respect international borders as inviolate for a long time.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] For example, the Organization of African Unity (OAU), which was established in 1963 and replaced by the African Union in 2002, set the respect for the territorial integrity of each country as one of its principles in OAU Charter.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Indeed, compared with the formation of European countries, there have been fewer international conflicts in Africa for changing the borders, which has influenced country formation there and has enabled some countries to survive that might have been defeated and absorbed by others.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Yet international conflicts have played out by support for proxy armies or rebel movements.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Many states have experienced civil wars: including Rwanda, Sudan, Angola, Sierra Leone, Congo, Liberia, Ethiopia and Somalia.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Wars of national liberation also often took up a Marxist, Marxist–Leninist, or Maoist character in ideological terms, where the independence of African nations was raised in Marxian terms.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Early examples included the Union of the Peoples of Cameroon armed movement against French colonialism, a Marxist–Leninist insurgency, followed by similar movements in Congo (the Simba Rebellion).
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Che Guevara participated in the latter, and opined in 1967 that Africa was not ready for revolution.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Despite this, in Zanzibar before and after unification with Tanzania, forms of socialism took hold.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Even after 1990, there are some examples of Military Marxism, such as a militia established by Ernest Wamba-dia-Wamba in Eastern Congo in the 1990s.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] The countries in this table are categorised according to the scheme for geographic subregions used by the United Nations, and data included are per sources in cross-referenced articles.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Where they differ, provisos are clearly indicated.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] This list contains nine territories that are administered as incorporated areas of a primarily non-African country but that belong geographically to the African continent.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] The continent's total nominal GDP remains behind that of several individual countries, including the United States, China, Japan, Germany, the United Kingdom, India and France.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] According to the United Nations' Human Development Report in 2003, the bottom 24 ranked nations (151st to 175th) were all African.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Poverty, illiteracy, malnutrition, inadequate water supply and sanitation, and poor health affect a large proportion of the people who reside on the African continent.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] In August 2008, the World Bank announced revised global poverty estimates based on a new international poverty line of $1.25 per day (versus the previous measure of $1.00).
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Eighty-one percent of the sub-Saharan African population was living on less than $2.50 (PPP) per day in 2005, compared with 86% for India.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Sub-Saharan Africa is the least successful region of the world in reducing poverty ($1.25 per day); some 50% of the population living in poverty in 1981 (200 million people), a figure that rose to 58% in 1996 before dropping to 50% in 2005 (380 million people).
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] The average poor person in sub-Saharan Africa is estimated to live on only 70 cents per day, and was poorer in 2003 than in 1973, indicating increasing poverty in some areas.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Some of it is attributed to unsuccessful economic liberalisation programmes spearheaded by foreign companies and governments, but other studies have cited bad domestic government policies more than external factors.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Africa is now at risk of being in debt once again, particularly in sub-Saharan African countries.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] The last debt crisis in 2005 was resolved with help from the heavily indebted poor countries scheme (HIPC).
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] The HIPC resulted in some positive and negative effects on the economy in Africa.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] About ten years after the 2005 debt crisis in sub-Saharan Africa was resolved, Zambia fell back into debt.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] A small reason was due to the fall in copper prices in 2011, but the bigger reason was that a large amount of the money Zambia borrowed was wasted or pocketed by the elite.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] From 1995 to 2005, Africa's rate of economic growth increased, averaging 5% in 2005.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Some countries experienced still higher growth rates, notably Angola, Sudan and Equatorial Guinea, all of which had recently begun extracting their petroleum reserves or had expanded their oil extraction capacity.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] The following table shows the projected nominal GDP and GDP per capita (at purchasing power parity) in 2026 by the IMF.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] The continent is believed to hold 90% of the world's cobalt, 90% of its platinum, 50% of its gold, 98% of its chromium, 70% of its tantalite, 64% of its manganese and one-third of its uranium.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] The Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) has 70% of the world's coltan, a mineral used in the production of tantalum capacitors for electronic devices such as cell phones.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] The DRC also has more than 30% of the world's diamond reserves.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Guinea is the world's largest exporter of bauxite.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] As the growth in Africa has been driven mainly by services and not manufacturing or agriculture, it has been growth without jobs and without reduction in poverty levels.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] In fact, the food security crisis of 2008, which took place following the global financial crisis, pushed 100 million people into food insecurity.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] In 2024 nearly 307 million people in Africa were undernourished (46% of the global total), an increase of 10 million people since 2023 and 34 million from 2022.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] In recent years, China has built increasingly stronger ties with African nations and is Africa's largest trading partner.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] In 2007, Chinese companies invested a total of US$1 billion in Africa.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] A Harvard University study led by professor Calestous Juma showed that Africa could feed itself by making the transition from importer to self-sufficiency.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] "African agriculture is at the crossroads; we have come to the end of a century of policies that favoured Africa's export of raw materials and importation of food.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Cooking with biogas in Tanzania; Geothermal energy infrastructure in Kenya; Coal power station in South Africa; Solar-powered lamp-light in Zambia.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Energy in Africa is characterised by low per-capita consumption and limited access to modern energy services, reflecting both infrastructural and socio-economic challenges across the continent.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] As of 2023, Africa accounted for just 5.5% of global total final energy consumption, with per-capita energy use more than three times lower than the global average.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] The energy mix is dominated by biofuels and waste, which make up 43% of total final consumption, primarily for household cooking and heating, followed by oil products at 33%, electricity at 11%, natural gas at 9%, and coal at 4%.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Electricity access remains a major challenge, particularly in Sub-Saharan Africa, where nearly 450 million rural residents lack reliable electricity, and grid coverage is often inconsistent.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Clean cooking solutions are similarly underdeveloped, leaving over 900 million people reliant on polluting fuels such as firewood, charcoal, and agricultural residues, which disproportionately affect women and children.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Transport energy is dominated by oil products, reflecting low motorisation rates and limited adoption of electric mobility, although countries such as Ethiopia, Morocco, and Egypt have begun adopting policies to reduce fossil fuel dependency.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Africa possesses some of the world's most abundant energy resources, including oil, natural gas, coal, hydropower, solar, wind, geothermal, and biomass, much of which remains underutilised.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] While fossil fuels such as coal, oil, and natural gas continue to dominate energy production and electricity generation in Africa, renewable sources are increasingly expanding across the continent.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Hydropower, solar, wind, geothermal, and modern biomass are growing in capacity, though their deployment remains uneven and limited compared to the continent's vast potential.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Hydropower is the largest non-combustible renewable source, while solar energy offers immense potential due to high irradiation levels, particularly in the Sahara and Sahel.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] There are regional differences: North Africa is dominated by oil and gas production, Southern Africa by coal and hydropower, East Africa by hydropower and geothermal, and West and Central Africa face major electrification gaps despite hydroelectric potential.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Water development and management are complex in Africa due to the multiplicity of trans-boundary water resources (rivers, lakes and aquifers).
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Around 75% of sub-Saharan Africa falls within 53 international river basin catchments that traverse multiple borders.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] This particular constraint can also be converted into an opportunity if the potential for trans-boundary cooperation is harnessed in the development of the area's water resources.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] A multi-sectoral analysis of the Zambezi River, for example, shows that riparian cooperation could lead to a 23% increase in firm energy production without any additional investments.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] A number of institutional and legal frameworks for transboundary cooperation exist, such as the Zambezi River Authority, the Southern African Development Community (SADC) Protocol, Volta River Authority and the Nile Basin Commission.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] However, additional efforts are required to further develop political will, as well as the financial capacities and institutional frameworks needed for win-win multilateral cooperative actions and optimal solutions for all riparians.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Africa is considered by anthropologists to be the most genetically diverse continent as a result of being the longest inhabited.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Africa's population has rapidly increased over the last 40 years, and is consequently relatively young.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] In some African states, more than half the population is under 25 years of age.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] The total number of people in Africa increased from 229 million in 1950 to 630 million in 1990.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] As of 2021, the population of Africa is estimated at 1,394 million.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Africa's total population surpassing other continents is fairly recent; African population surpassed Europe in the 1990s, while the Americas was overtaken sometime around the year 2000.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] This increase in number of babies born in Africa compared to the rest of the world is expected to reach approximately 37% in the year 2050; while in 1990 sub-Saharan Africa accounted for only 16% of the world's births.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] The total fertility rate (children per woman) for Sub-Saharan Africa is 4.7 as of 2018, the highest in the world.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] All countries in sub-Saharan Africa had TFRs (average number of children) above replacement level in 2019 and accounted for 27.1% of global livebirths.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] In 2021, sub-Saharan Africa accounted for 29% of global births.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Speakers of Bantu languages (part of the Niger–Congo family) are the majority in southern, central and southeast Africa.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] The Bantu-speaking peoples from the Sahel progressively expanded over most of sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] But there are also several Nilotic groups in South Sudan and East Africa, the mixed Swahili people on the Swahili Coast, and a few remaining indigenous Khoisan ("San" or "Bushmen") and Pygmy peoples in Southern and Central Africa, respectively.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Bantu-speaking Africans also predominate in Gabon and Equatorial Guinea, and are found in parts of southern Cameroon.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] In the Kalahari Desert of Southern Africa, the distinct people known as the Bushmen (also "San", closely related to, but distinct from "Hottentots") have long been present.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] The San are physically distinct from other Africans and are the indigenous people of southern Africa.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Pygmies are the pre-Bantu indigenous peoples of central Africa.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] The peoples of West Africa primarily speak Niger–Congo languages, belonging mostly to its non-Bantu branches, though some Nilo-Saharan and Afro-Asiatic speaking groups are also found.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] The Niger–Congo-speaking Yoruba, Igbo, Fulani, Akan, and Wolof ethnic groups are the largest and most influential.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] In the central Sahara, Mandinka or Mande groups are most significant.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Chadic-speaking groups, including the Hausa, are found in more northerly parts of the region nearest to the Sahara, and Nilo-Saharan communities, such as the Songhai, Kanuri, and Zarma, are found in the eastern parts of West Africa bordering Central Africa.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] The peoples of North Africa consist of three main indigenous groups: Berbers in the northwest, Egyptians in the northeast, and Nilo-Saharan-speaking peoples in the east.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] The Arabs who arrived in the 7th century AD introduced the Arabic language and Islam to North Africa.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] The Semitic Phoenicians (who founded Carthage) and Hyksos, the Indo-Iranian Alans, the Indo-European Greeks, Romans, and Vandals settled in North Africa as well.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Significant Berber communities remain within Morocco and Algeria in the 21st century, while, to a lesser extent, Berber speakers are also present in some regions of Tunisia and Libya.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] The Berber-speaking Tuareg and other often-nomadic peoples are the principal inhabitants of the Saharan interior of North Africa.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] In Mauritania, there is a small but near-extinct Berber community in the north and Niger–Congo-speaking peoples in the south, though in both regions Arabic and Arab culture predominates.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] In Sudan, although Arabic and Arab culture predominate, it is mostly inhabited by groups that originally spoke Nilo-Saharan, such as the Nubians, Fur, Masalit and Zaghawa, who, over the centuries, have variously intermixed with migrants from the Arabian peninsula.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Small communities of Afro-Asiatic-speaking Beja nomads can also be found in Egypt and Sudan.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] In the Horn of Africa, some Ethiopian and Eritrean groups (like the Amhara and Tigrayans, collectively known as Habesha) speak languages from the Semitic branch of the Afro-Asiatic language family, while the Oromo and Somali speak languages from the Cushitic branch of Afro-Asiatic.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Prior to the decolonisation movements of the post-World War II era, Europeans were represented in every part of Africa.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Decolonization during the 1960s and 1970s often resulted in the mass emigration of white settlers—especially from Algeria and Morocco (1.6 million *pieds-noirs* in North Africa), Kenya, Congo, Rhodesia, Mozambique and Angola.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Between 1975 and 1977, over a million colonials returned to Portugal alone.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Nevertheless, white Africans remain an important minority in many African states, particularly Zimbabwe, Namibia, Réunion, and South Africa.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] The country with the largest white African population is South Africa.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Dutch and British diasporas represent the largest communities of European ancestry on the continent today.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] European colonisation also brought sizable groups of Asians, particularly from the Indian subcontinent, to British colonies.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Large Indian communities are found in South Africa, and smaller ones are present in Kenya, Tanzania, and some other southern and southeast African countries.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] The large Indian community in Uganda was expelled by the dictator Idi Amin in 1972, though many have since returned.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] The islands in the Indian Ocean are also populated primarily by people of Asian origin, often mixed with Africans and Europeans.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] The Malagasy people of Madagascar are an Austronesian people, but those along the coast are generally mixed with Bantu, Arab, Indian and European origins.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Malay and Indian ancestries are also important components in the group of people known in South Africa as Cape Coloureds (people with origins in two or more races and continents).
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] During the 20th century, small but economically important communities of Lebanese have also developed in the larger coastal cities of West and East Africa, respectively.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] The Sahara served as a trans-regional passageway and place of dwelling for people in Africa during various humid phases and periods throughout the history of Africa.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] As early as 11,000 years ago, Sub-Saharan West Africans, bearing macrohaplogroup L (e.g., L1b1a11, L1b1a6a, L1b1a8, L1b1a9a1, L2a1k, L3d1b1a), may have migrated through North Africa and into Europe, mostly into southern Europe (e.g., Iberia).
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] The genetic marker E1b1 was identified to have wide distribution across Egypt, with "P2/215/M35.1 (E1b1b), for short M35, likely also originated in eastern tropical Africa, and is predominantly distributed in an arc from the Horn of Africa up through Egypt".
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] The R haplogroup has also been identified to have high frequencies in central Saharan Africa, among some Afro-Asiatic and Nilo-Saharan language speaking groups.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Genetic evidence has identified the Horn of Africa to be the source of a genetic marker "M35/215" Y-chromosome lineage for a significant population component which moved north from that region into Egypt and the Levant.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Historian Christopher Ehret argued that this genetic distribution paralleled the spread of the Afrasian language family with the movement of people from the Horn of Africa into Egypt and added a new demic component to the existing population of Egypt 17,000 years ago.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] According to a recent study, the Arab migrations to the Maghreb was mainly a demographic process that heavily implied gene flow and remodelled the genetic structure of the Maghreb region in North Africa, rather than a mere cultural replacement as claimed by older studies.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Another study found out that the majority of J-M267 (Eu10) chromosomes in the Maghreb are due to the recent gene flow caused by the Arab migrations to the Maghreb in the first millennium CE as both southern Qahtanite and northern Adnanite Arabs added to the heterogenous Maghrebi ethnic melting pot.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] The Eu10 chromosome pool in the Maghreb is derived not only from early Neolithic dispersions from Western Asia but to a much greater extent from recent expansions of Arab tribes from the Arabian Peninsula.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] David Schoenbrun, Christopher Ehret, Steven A.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Brandt and Shomarka Keita (2025) have highlighted the problematic categorisation of genetic haplogroups characterised as ‘African’ and ‘Eurasian' in North African genome studies.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] In reference to the van de Loosdrecht et al.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] In their view, identifying a range of African populations may still remain an issue “since the idea of ‘African’ still gets stereotyped or restricted.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] (Accepting the southwestern Asian/Levantine geographical continuity with Africa eliminates a conceptual barrier related to racio-typological thinking permitting an Africasian construct analogous to Eurasian.)”.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] While Africans profess a wide variety of religious beliefs, the majority of the people respect African religions or parts of them.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] However, in formal surveys or census, most people will identify with major religions that came from outside the continent, mainly through colonisation.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] There are several reasons for this, the main one being the colonial idea that African religious beliefs and practices are not good enough.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Religious beliefs and statistics on religious affiliation are difficult to come by since they are often a sensitive topic for governments with mixed religious populations.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] According to the *World Book Encyclopedia*, Islam and Christianity are the two largest religions in Africa.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Islam is most prevalent in Northern Africa, and is the state religion of many North African countries, such as Algeria, where 99% of the population practices Islam.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] The majority of people in most governments in Southern, Southeast, and Central Africa, as well as in a sizable portion of the Horn of Africa and West Africa, identify as Christians.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] The Coptic Christians constitute a sizable minority in Egypt, and the Ethiopian Orthodox Church is the largest church in Ethiopia, with 36 million and 51 million adherents.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] According to Encyclopædia Britannica, 45% of the population are Christians, 40% are Muslims, and 10% follow traditional religions.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] A small number of Africans are Hindu, Buddhist, Confucianist, Baháʼí, or Jewish.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] There is also a minority of people in Africa who are irreligious.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] By most estimates, well over a thousand languages (UNESCO has estimated around two thousand) are spoken in Africa.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Most are of African origin, though some are of European or Asian origin.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Africa is the most multilingual continent in the world, and it is not rare for individuals to fluently speak not only multiple African languages, but one or more European ones as well.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Following the end of colonialism, nearly all African countries adopted official languages that originated outside the continent, although several countries also granted legal recognition to indigenous languages (such as Swahili, Yoruba, Igbo and Hausa).
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] In numerous countries, English and French (*see African French*) are used for communication in the public sphere such as government, commerce, education and the media.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Arabic, Portuguese, Afrikaans and Spanish are examples of languages that trace their origin to outside of Africa, and that are used by millions of Africans today, both in the public and private spheres.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Italian is spoken by some in former Italian colonies in Africa.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] German is spoken in Namibia, as it was a former German protectorate.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] In total, at least a fifth of Africans speak the former colonial languages.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Moreover, in recent years some African countries have been considering removing their official former colonial languages, such as Mali, Burkina Faso and Niger which removed French as an official language in the 2020s in favour of native languages, while also renaming colonial street names.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] More than 85% of individuals in Africa use traditional medicine as an alternative to often expensive allopathic medical health care and costly pharmaceutical products.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] AIDS in post-colonial Africa is a prevalent issue.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Although the continent is home to about 15.2 percent of the world's population, more than two-thirds of the total infected worldwide—some 35 million people—were Africans, of whom 15 million have already died.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Sub-Saharan Africa alone accounted for an estimated 69 percent of all people living with HIV and 70 percent of all AIDS deaths in 2011.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] In the countries of sub-Saharan Africa most affected, AIDS has raised death rates and lowered life expectancy among adults between the ages of 20 and 49 by about twenty years.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p02] Furthermore, the life expectancy in many parts of Africa has declined, largely as a result of the HIV/AIDS epidemic with life-expectancy in some countries reaching as low as thirty-four years.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] Africa is divided into a great number of ethnic cultures.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] In recent times, the call for a much greater emphasis on the cultural dimension in all aspects of development has become increasingly vocal.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] Some aspects of traditional African cultures have become less practised in recent years as a result of neglect and suppression by colonial and post-colonial regimes.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] For example, African customs were discouraged, and African languages were prohibited in mission schools, while colonialists such as Leopold II of Belgium attempted to "civilize" Africans by discouraging polygamy and witchcraft.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] Abiola Irele and Simon Gikandi comment that the current identity of African literature had its genesis in the "traumatic encounter between Africa and Europe".
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] On the other hand, Mhoze Chikowero believes that Africans deployed music, dance, spirituality, and other performative cultures to (re)assert themselves as active agents and indigenous intellectuals, to unmake their colonial marginalisation and reshape their own destinies.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] As of March 2023, 98 African properties are listed by UNESCO as World Heritage Sites.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] Among these proprieties, 54 are cultural sites, 39 are natural sites and 5 are mixed sites.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] The List of World Heritage in Danger includes 15 African sites.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] African art refers to works of visual art, including works of sculpture, painting, metalwork, and pottery, originating from the various peoples of the African continent and influenced by distinct, indigenous traditions of aesthetic expression.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] While the various artistic traditions of such a large and diverse continent display considerable regional and cultural variety, there are consistent artistic themes, recurring motifs, and unifying elements across the broad spectrum of the African visual expression.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] As is the case for every artistic tradition in human history, African art was created within specific social, political, and religious contexts.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] Likewise, African art was often created not purely for art's sake, but rather with some practical, spiritual, and/or didactic purpose in mind.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] In general, African art prioritizes conceptual and symbolic representation over realism, aiming to visualize the subject's spiritual essence.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] Ethiopian art, heavily influenced by Ethiopia's long-standing Christian tradition, is also different from most African art, where Traditional African religion (with Islam prevalent in the north east and north west presently) was dominant until the 20th century.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] African art includes prehistoric and ancient art, the Islamic art of West Africa, the Christian art of East Africa, and the traditional artifacts of these and other regions.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] Many African sculptures were historically made of wood and other natural materials that have not survived from earlier than a few centuries ago, although rare older pottery and metal figures can be found in some areas.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] Some of the earliest decorative objects, such as shell beads and evidence of paint, have been discovered in Africa, dating to the Middle Stone Age.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] Masks are important elements in the art of many people, along with human figures, and are often highly stylized.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] There exist diverse styles, which can often be observed within a single context of origin and may be influenced by the intended use of the object.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] Nevertheless, broad regional trends are discernible.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] Sculpture is most common among "groups of settled cultivators in the areas drained by the Niger and Congo rivers" in West Africa.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] Direct images of deities are relatively infrequent, but masks in particular are or were often made for ritual ceremonies.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] Since the late 19th century, there has been an increasing amount of African art in Western collections, the finest pieces of which are displayed as part of the history of colonization.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] African art had an important influence on European Modernist art, which was inspired by their interest in abstract depiction.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] It was this appreciation of African sculpture that has been attributed to the very concept of "African art", as seen by European and American artists and art historians.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] Obidoh Freeborn posits that colonialism is one element that has created the character of modern African art.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] According to authors Douglas Fraser and Herbert M.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] Author Chika Okeke-Agulu states that "the racist infrastructure of British imperial enterprise forced upon the political and cultural guardians of empire a denial and suppression of an emergent sovereign Africa and modernist art".
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] scaling: small parts of the structure tend to look similar to larger parts, such as a circular village made of circular houses.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] African architecture in some areas has been influenced by external cultures for centuries, according to available evidence.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] Western architecture has influenced coastal areas since the late 15th century and is now an important source of inspiration for many larger buildings, particularly in major cities.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] African architecture uses a wide range of materials, including thatch, stick/wood, mud, mudbrick, rammed earth, and stone.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] These material preferences vary by region: North Africa for stone and rammed earth, the Horn of Africa for stone and mortar, West Africa for mud/adobe, Central Africa for thatch/wood and more perishable materials, Southeast and Southern Africa for stone and thatch/wood.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] Cinema of Africa refers to the film industries and films produced in the continent of Africa.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] It covers both the history and present of the making or screening of films on the African continent, and also refers to the persons involved in this form of audiovisual culture.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] It dates back to the late 19th century, when film reels were the primary cinematic technology in use.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] Cairo has been the capital of film industry in Africa since the early 20th century to the present day.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] As there are more than 50 countries with audiovisual traditions, there is no one single 'African cinema'.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] Both historically and culturally, there are major regional differences between North African and sub-Saharan cinemas, and between the cinemas of different countries.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] The Egyptian film industry and the Tunisian are also among the oldest in the world.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] Cinema of Egypt in particular is the most established and flourishing industry in Africa.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] Pioneers Auguste and Louis Lumière screened their films in Alexandria, Cairo, Tunis, Susa, Libya and Hammam-Lif, Tunisia in 1896.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] Albert Samama Chikly is often cited as the first producer of indigenous African cinema, screening his own short documentaries in the casino of Tunis as early as December 1905.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] The continent of Africa and its music is vast and highly diverse, with different regions and nations maintaining distinct musical traditions.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] African music includes genres such as makwaya, highlife, mbube, township music, jùjú, fuji, jaiva, afrobeat, afrofusion, mbalax, Congolese rumba, soukous, ndombolo, makossa, kizomba, and taarab, among others.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] African music also uses a wide variety of instruments from across the continent.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] The music and dance traditions of the African diaspora, shaped to varying degrees by African musical traditions, include American genres such as Dixieland jazz, blues, and jazz, as well as Caribbean styles such as calypso (see kaiso), and soca.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] Latin American music genres including cumbia, salsa, son cubano, rumba, conga, bomba, samba, and zouk developed from the music of enslaved Africans and have, in turn, influenced contemporary African popular music.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] African dance (also Afro dance, Afrodance and Afro-dance) refers to the various dance styles of sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] These dances are closely connected with the traditional rhythms and music traditions of the region.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] Music and dancing is an integral part of many traditional African societies.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] Songs and dances facilitate teaching and promoting social values, the celebration of special events and major life milestones, the performance of oral history and other recitations, and spiritual experiences.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] African dance uses the concepts of polyrhythm and total body articulation.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] African dances are often a collective activity performed in large groups, with significant interaction between dancers and onlookers.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] Fifty-four African countries have football teams in the Confederation of African Football.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] Egypt has won the African Cup seven times, and a record-making three times in a row.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] Cameroon, Nigeria, Morocco, Senegal, Ghana, and Algeria have advanced to the knockout stage of recent FIFA World Cups.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] Morocco, at the 2022 World Cup in Qatar was the first African nation to reach the semi-finals of the FIFA Men's World Cup.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] South Africa hosted the 2010 World Cup tournament, becoming the first African country to do so.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] The top clubs in each African football league play the CAF Champions League, while lower-ranked clubs compete in CAF Confederation Cup.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] In recent years, the continent has progressed in terms of state-of-the-art basketball facilities, which have been built in cities such as Cairo, Dakar, Johannesburg, Kigali, Luanda, and Rades.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] The number of African basketball players who drafted into the U.S.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] NBA has experienced growth in the 2010s.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] Cricket is popular in some African nations.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] South Africa and Zimbabwe have Test status, while Kenya is the leading non-test team and previously had One-Day International cricket (ODI) status (from 10 October 1997, until 30 January 2014).
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] The three countries jointly hosted the 2003 Cricket World Cup.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] Namibia is the other African country to have played in a World Cup.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] Morocco, in northern Africa, hosted the 2002 Morocco Cup, but the national team has never qualified for a major tournament.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] Rugby is popular in several southern African nations.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] Namibia and Zimbabwe have appeared on multiple occasions at the Rugby World Cup, while South Africa is the most successful national team at the Rugby World Cup, having won the tournament on four occasions, in 1995, 2007, 2019, and 2023.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] Traditional sports were strictly marginalised during the colonial era, and many are dying or have gone extinct under the pressure of modernisation, however lots remain popular despite not having formal governmental recognition or support.
[src:mudbrick/africa-p03] Some examples are Senegalese wrestling, Dambe, Nguni stick-fighting, and Savika.
[src:mudbrick/alligator-drum] The **alligator drum** (simplified Chinese: 鼍鼓; traditional Chinese: 鼉鼓; pinyin: *tuó gǔ*) is a type of drum once used in Neolithic China, made from clay and alligator hides.
[src:mudbrick/alligator-drum] Alligator drums have been found over a broad area at the Neolithic sites from modern Shandong in the east to Qinghai in the west, dating to a period of 5500–2350 BC.
[src:mudbrick/alligator-drum] In literary records, drums manifested shamanistic characteristics and were often used in ritual ceremonies.
[src:mudbrick/alligator-drum] Drums covered with alligator skin for ceremonial use are mentioned in the *Shijing*.
[src:mudbrick/alligator-drum] During the Archaic period, alligators probably lived along the east coast of China, including southern Shandong.
[src:mudbrick/alligator-drum] The earliest alligator drums, comprising a wooden frame covered with alligator skin, are found in the archaeological sites at Dawenkou, as well as several sites of Longshan.
[src:mudbrick/alligator-drum] Typical acoustic characteristics of the alligator drum are as follows: frequency: 4100–2600 Hz, amplitude: 3000–2000 dB, and wavelength: 2300–1900 Hz.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] The site is on the east bank of the Nile River, in what today is the Egyptian province of Minya.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] It is about 58 km (36 mi) south of the city of al-Minya, 312 km (194 mi) south of the Egyptian capital, Cairo, and 402 km (250 mi) north of Luxor (site of the previous capital, Thebes).
[src:mudbrick/amarna] The city of Deir Mawas lies directly to its west.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] On the east side of Amarna there are several modern villages, the chief of which are l-Till in the north and el-Hagg Qandil in the south.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] Activity in the region flourished from the Amarna Period until the later Roman era.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] The name *Amarna* comes from the Beni Amran, an Arab tribe that settled the area before the 18th century.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] The ancient Egyptian name Akhetaten means "the horizon of the Aten".
[src:mudbrick/amarna] The area of the city was effectively a virgin site, and it was this city that Akhenaten described as the Aten's "seat of the First Occasion, which he had made for himself that he might rest in it".
[src:mudbrick/amarna] It may be that the Royal Wadi's resemblance to the hieroglyph for *horizon* showed that this was the place to found the city.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] The city was built as the new capital of the Pharaoh Akhenaten, dedicated to his new religion of worship to the Aten.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] Construction started in or around Year 5 of his reign (1346 BC) and was probably completed by Year 9 (1341 BC), although it became the capital city two years earlier.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] To speed up construction of the city most of the buildings were constructed out of mudbrick, and white washed.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] The most important buildings were faced with local stone.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] It is the only ancient Egyptian city which preserves great details of its internal plan in large part because it was abandoned almost completely shortly after the royal government of Tutankhamun quit the city in favor of Thebes (modern Luxor).
[src:mudbrick/amarna] The city seems to have remained active for a decade or so after his death, and a shrine to Horemheb indicates that it was at least partially occupied at the beginning of his reign, if only as a source for building material elsewhere.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] Once it was abandoned, it remained uninhabited until Roman settlement began along the edge of the Nile.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] However, due to the unique circumstances of its creation and abandonment, it is questionable how representative of ancient Egyptian cities it actually is.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] Amarna was hastily constructed and covered an area of approximately 8 miles (13 km) of territory on the east bank of the Nile River; on the west bank, land was set aside to provide crops for the city's population.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] The entire city is encircled with a total of 14 boundary stelae (labeled A thru V with discontinuities left for those thought to be missing, Stele B was defaced by locals in 1885) detailing Akhenaten's conditions for the establishment of this new capital city of Egypt.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] The earliest dated stele from Akhenaten's new city is known to be *Boundary stele K* which is dated to Year 5, IV Peret (or month 8), day 13 of Akhenaten's reign.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] (Most of the original 14 boundary stelae have been badly eroded.) It preserves an account of Akhenaten's foundation of this city.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] Located on the east bank of the Nile, the ruins of the city are laid out roughly north to south along a "Royal Road", now referred to as "Sikhet es-Sultan".
[src:mudbrick/amarna] The Royal residences are generally to the north, in what is known as the North City, with a central administration and religious area and the south of the city is made up of residential suburbs.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] If one approached the city of Amarna from the north by river the first buildings past the northern boundary stele would be the North Riverside Palace.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] This building ran all the way up to the waterfront and was likely the main residence of the royal family.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] Located within the North City area is the Northern Palace, the main residence of the royal family.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] Between this and the central city, the Northern Suburb was initially a prosperous area with large houses, but the house size decreased and became poorer the further from the road they were.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] The **North City** was an administrative area.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] It contains the ruins of royal palaces, especially the Northern Palace and other administrative buildings and occupies an area between the river and the cliffs that terminate the plains to the north of the city itself.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] Most of the important ceremonial and administrative buildings were located in the central city.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] Here the Great Temple of the Aten and the Small Aten Temple were used for religious functions and between these the Great Royal Palace and Royal Residence were the ceremonial residence of the king and royal family, and were linked by a bridge or ramp.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] Located behind the Royal Residence was the Bureau of Correspondence of Pharaoh, where the Amarna Letters were found.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] This area was probably the first area to be completed, and had at least two phases of construction.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] To the south of the city was the area now referred to as the *Southern Suburbs*.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] It contained the estates of many of the city's powerful nobles, including Nakhtpaaten (Chief Minister), Ranefer, Panehesy (High Priest of the Aten), and Ramose (Master of Horses).
[src:mudbrick/amarna] This area also held the studio of the sculptor Thutmose, where the famous bust of Nefertiti was found in 1912.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] Surrounding the city and marking its extent, the Boundary Stelae (each a rectangle of carved rock on the cliffs on both sides of the Nile) describing the founding of the city are a primary source of information about it.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] Away from the city Akhenaten's Royal necropolis was started in a narrow valley to the east of the city, hidden in the cliffs.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] Only one tomb was completed, and was used by an unnamed Royal Wife, and Akhenaten's tomb was hastily used to hold him and likely Meketaten, his second daughter.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] In the cliffs to the north and south of the Royal Wadi, the nobles of the city constructed their Tombs.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] Much of what is known about Amarna's founding is due to the preservation of a series of official boundary stelae (13 are known) ringing the perimeter of the city.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] These are cut into the cliffs on both sides of the Nile (10 on the east, 3 on the west) and record the events of Akhetaten (Amarna) from founding to just before its fall.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] To make the move from Thebes to Amarna, Akhenaten needed the support of the military.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] Ay, one of Akhenaten's principal advisors, exercised great influence in this area because his father Yuya had been an important military leader.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] Additionally, everyone in the military had grown up together; they had been a part of the richest and most successful period in Egypt's history under Akhenaten's father, so loyalty among the ranks was strong and unwavering.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] In 1887, a local woman digging for *sebakh* uncovered a cache of over 300 cuneiform tablets (now commonly known as the Amarna Letters).
[src:mudbrick/amarna] These tablets recorded select diplomatic correspondence of the Pharaoh and were predominantly written in Akkadian, the *lingua franca* commonly used during the Late Bronze Age of the Ancient Near East for such communication.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] This discovery led to the recognition of the importance of the site, and led to a further increase in exploration.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] The Amarna art-style broke with long-established Egyptian conventions.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] Unlike the strict idealistic formalism of previous Egyptian art, it depicted its subjects more realistically.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] These included informal scenes, such as intimate portrayals of affection within the royal family or playing with their children, and no longer portrayed women as lighter coloured than men.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] The art also had a realism that sometimes borders on caricature.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] While the worship of Aten was later referred to as the Amarna heresy and suppressed, this art had a more lasting legacy.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] The first western mention of the city was made in 1714 by Claude Sicard, a French Jesuit priest who was travelling through the Nile Valley who described the site and made a crude sketch of Stela A.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] As with much of Egypt, it was visited by Napoleon's *corps de savants* in 1798–1799, who prepared the first detailed map of Amarna, which was subsequently published in *Description de l'Égypte* between 1821 and 1830.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] After this European exploration continued in 1824 when Sir John Gardiner Wilkinson explored and mapped the city remains.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] The copyist Robert Hay and his surveyor G.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] Laver visited the locality and uncovered several of the Southern Tombs from sand drifts, recording the reliefs in 1833.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] The copies made by Hay and Laver languish largely unpublished in the British Library, where an ongoing project to identify their locations is underway.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] The Prussian expedition led by Richard Lepsius visited the site in 1843 and 1845, and recorded the visible monuments and topography of Amarna in two separate visits over a total of twelve days, using drawings and paper squeezes.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] The results included an improved map of the city.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] Despite being somewhat limited in accuracy, the engraved *Denkmäler* plates formed the basis for scholastic knowledge and interpretation of many of the scenes and inscriptions in the private tombs and some of the Boundary Stelae for the rest of the century.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] The records made by these early explorers teams are of immense importance since many of these remains were later destroyed or otherwise lost.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] Between 1891 and 1892 Alessandro Barsanti and Urbain Bouriant partly cleared the robbed out king's tomb.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] In 1891 and 1892 Sir Flinders Petrie worked for one season at Amarna, working independently of the Egypt Exploration Fund.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] He excavated primarily in the Central City, investigating the Great Temple of the Aten, the Great Official Palace, the King's House, the Bureau of Correspondence of Pharaoh, and several private houses.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] Although frequently amounting to little more than a sondage, Petrie's excavations revealed additional cuneiform tablets, the remains of several glass factories, and a great quantity of discarded faience, glass, and ceramic in sifting the palace rubbish heaps (including Mycenaean sherds).
[src:mudbrick/amarna] By publishing his results and reconstructions rapidly, Petrie was able to stimulate further interest in the site's potential.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] The copyist and artist Norman de Garis Davies published drawn and photographic descriptions of private tombs and boundary stelae from Amarna from 1903 to 1908.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] From 1907 until 1914 the Deutsche Orientgesellschaft expedition, led by Ludwig Borchardt, worked extensively throughout the North and South suburbs of the city.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] The first several years were spent doing survey work with excavation beginning in 1911.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] The famous bust of Nefertiti, now in Berlin's Ägyptisches Museum, was discovered amongst other sculptural artefacts in the workshop of the sculptor Thutmose.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] The outbreak of the First World War in August 1914 terminated the German excavations.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] In two seasons between 1923 and 1925 an Egypt Exploration Society expedition returned to excavation at Amarna under the direction of T.E.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] Peet, Sir Leonard Woolley, Henri Frankfort, Stephen Glanville, and John Pendlebury.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] Mary Chubb served as the digs administrator.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] The renewed investigations were focused on religious and royal structures.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] Their work resumed in two seasons between 1930 and 1932.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] Excavation resumed in the 1977 under with the Amarna Survey directed by Barry J.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] Kemp with the University of Cambridge and Amarna Expedition under Salvatore Garfi under the auspices of the Egypt Exploration Society and continued until 1982.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] Work was curtailed at that point due to regional conditions but resumed in 1996 under the Amarna Project and still under the direction of Barry J.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] In the 2000 season work also included the nearby archaeological site of Kom el-Nana and the start of a GPS survey of the region around Amarna.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] Much of the work during this period was at the house of the king's chief charioteer, Ranefer which had been partially excavated in 1921.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] A separate expedition led by Geoffrey Martin described and copied the reliefs from the Royal Tomb, later publishing its findings together with objects thought to have come from the tomb.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] Excavation at Amarna, under Amarna Project, continues to the present.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] Work includes excavation at a cemetery, close to the southern tombs of the Nobles and at several other cemeteries of private individuals.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] In the past years *National Geographic* and archaeological articles have published articles on Amarna, Akhenaten, Tutankhamun, or Nefertiti.
[src:mudbrick/amarna] Most of the article can be found in both the paperback or on the National Geographic website (currently the most recent article was published January 2021).
[src:mudbrick/mudbrick] A **mudbrick** (or **mud-brick**), also called an **unfired brick**, is an air-dried brick composed of a mixture of mud (containing loam, clay, sand, and water) with a binding material, such as rice husks or straw.
[src:mudbrick/mudbrick] Mudbricks are known to have been used since 9000 BCE.
[src:mudbrick/mudbrick] From around 5000–4000 BCE, mudbricks evolved into fired bricks to increase strength and durability.
[src:mudbrick/mudbrick] Nevertheless, in some warm regions with very little timber available to fuel a kiln, mudbricks continued to be in use.
[src:mudbrick/mudbrick] Mudbricks remain the modern standard of vernacular architecture in some warmer regions, mainly in parts of Africa and western Asia.
[src:mudbrick/mudbrick] In the 20th century, the compressed earth block was developed using high pressure as a cheap and eco-friendly alternative to obtain non-fired bricks with more strength than the simpler air-dried mudbricks.
[src:mudbrick/mudbrick] The history of mudbrick production and construction in the southern Levant may be dated as far back as the Pre-Pottery Neolithic A (e.g., PPNA Jericho).
[src:mudbrick/mudbrick] These sun dried mudbricks, also known as adobe or just mudbrick, were made from a mixture of sand, clay, water, frequently tempered with chopped straw and chaff branches, and were the most common material for constructing earthen buildings throughout the ancient Near East for millennia.
[src:mudbrick/mudbrick] Unfired mudbrick is still made throughout the world, using both modern and traditional methods.
[src:mudbrick/mudbrick] The 9000 BCE dwellings of Jericho were constructed from mudbricks, affixed with mud, as were those at numerous sites across the Levant over the following millennia.
[src:mudbrick/mudbrick] Well-preserved mudbricks from a site at Tel Tsaf, in the Jordan Valley, have been dated to 5200 BCE, though there is no evidence that this site was the first to use the technology.
[src:mudbrick/mudbrick] Evidence suggests that the mudbrick composition at Tel Tsaf was stable for at least 500 years, throughout the middle Chalcolithic period.
[src:mudbrick/mudbrick] The South Asian inhabitants of Mehrgarh constructed and lived in mudbrick houses between 7000 and 3300 BCE.
[src:mudbrick/mudbrick] Mudbricks were used at more than 15 reported sites attributed to the 3rd millennium BCE in the ancient Indus Valley civilization.
[src:mudbrick/mudbrick] In the Mature Harappan phase, fired bricks were used.
[src:mudbrick/mudbrick] The Mesopotamians used sun-dried bricks in their city construction; typically these bricks were flat on the bottom and curved on the top, called plano-convex mudbricks.
[src:mudbrick/mudbrick] Some were formed in a square mould and rounded so that the middle was thicker than the ends.
[src:mudbrick/mudbrick] Some walls had a few courses of fired bricks from their bases up to the splash line to extend the life of the building.
[src:mudbrick/mudbrick] In Minoan Crete, at the Knossos site, there is archaeological evidence that sun-dried bricks were used in the Neolithic period (prior to 3400 BCE).
[src:mudbrick/mudbrick] Sun-dried mudbricks were the most common construction material employed in ancient Egypt during pharaonic times and were made in pretty much the same way for millennia.
[src:mudbrick/mudbrick] Mud from some locations required sand, chopped straw, or other binders such as animal dung to be mixed in with the mud to increase durability and plasticity.
[src:mudbrick/mudbrick] Workers gathered mud from the Nile river and poured it into a pit.
[src:mudbrick/mudbrick] Workers then tramped on the mud while straw was added to solidify the mold.
[src:mudbrick/mudbrick] The mudbricks were chemically suitable as fertilizer, leading to the destruction of many ancient Egyptian ruins, such as at Edfu; one well-preserved site is Amarna.
[src:mudbrick/mudbrick] Mudbrick use increased during the time of Roman influence.
[src:mudbrick/mudbrick] In the Ancient Greek world, mudbrick was commonly used for the building of walls, fortifications and citadels, such as the walls of the Citadel of Troy (Troy II).
[src:mudbrick/mudbrick] These mudbricks were often made with straw or dried vegetable matter.
[src:mudbrick/mudbrick] In areas of Spanish influence, mudbrick construction is called adobe, and developed over time into a complete system of wall protection, flat roofing and finishes which in modern English usage is often referred to as "adobe style", regardless of the construction method.
[src:mudbrick/mudbrick] The Great Mosque of Djenné, in central Mali, is the world's largest mudbrick structure.
[src:mudbrick/mudbrick] It, like much of Sahelian architecture, is built with a mudbrick called **Banco**, a recipe of mud and grain husks, fermented, and either formed into bricks or applied on surfaces as a plaster like paste in broad strokes.
[src:mudbrick/mudbrick] This plaster must be reapplied annually.
[src:mudbrick/mudbrick] In some cases, brickmakers extended the life of mudbricks by putting fired bricks on top or covering them with stucco.
